# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alfred-schütz
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was born in Braunau am Inn in Austria-Hungary and moved to Germany in 1913.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He was decorated during his service in the German Army in the First World War, receiving the Iron Cross.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1919, he joined the German Workers' Party (DAP), the precursor of the Nazi Party, and in 1921, was appointed the leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, he attempted to seize governmental power in a failed coup in Munich and was sentenced to five years in prison, serving just over a year.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, he dictated the first volume of his autobiography and political manifesto *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] After his early release in 1924, he gained popular support by attacking the Treaty of Versailles as well as promoting pan-Germanism, antisemitism, and anti-communism with charismatic oratory and Nazi propaganda.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He frequently denounced communism as being part of an international Jewish conspiracy.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] By November 1932, the Nazi Party held the most seats in the *Reichstag*, but not a majority.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Former chancellor Franz von Papen and other conservative politicians convinced President Paul von Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as chancellor on 30 January 1933.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly thereafter, on 23 March, the *Reichstag* passed the Enabling Act of 1933, which ultimately began the Weimar Republic's transformation into Nazi Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Upon Hindenburg's death on 2 August 1934, Hitler replaced him as head of state and thereafter transformed Germany into a totalitarian dictatorship.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Domestically, Hitler implemented numerous racist policies and sought to deport or kill German Jews.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] His first six years in power resulted in rapid economic recovery from the Great Depression, the abrogation of restrictions imposed on Germany after the First World War, and the annexation of territories inhabited by millions of ethnic Germans, which initially gave him significant popular support.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] One of Hitler's key goals was *Lebensraum* (lit.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] 'living space') for the German people in Eastern Europe.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] His aggressive, expansionist foreign policy is considered the primary cause of World War II in Europe.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 September 1939, Hitler oversaw the German invasion of Poland, thereby causing Britain and France to declare war on Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] After ordering an invasion of the Soviet Union in June 1941, he declared war on the United States in December of the same year.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of 1941, German forces and the European Axis powers occupied most of Europe and North Africa.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] These gains were gradually reversed after 1941 until the Allied forces defeated the German military in 1945.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 29 April 1945, Hitler married his longtime partner, Eva Braun, in the *Führerbunker* in Berlin.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] They committed suicide the next day to avoid capture by the Soviet Red Army.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The historian and biographer Ian Kershaw described Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Under Hitler's leadership and racist ideology, the Nazi regime was responsible for the genocide of an estimated six million Jews and millions of other victims, whom he and his followers deemed *Untermenschen* (lit.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazis were also responsible for the deliberate killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of civilians killed during World War II was unprecedented in warfare, and the casualties make it the deadliest conflict in history.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's father, Alois Hitler, was the illegitimate child of Maria Schicklgruber.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The baptismal register did not show the name of his father, and Alois initially bore his mother's surname, "Schicklgruber".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1842, Johann Georg Hiedler married Alois's mother.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was brought up in the family of Hiedler's brother, Johann Nepomuk Hiedler.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois worked as a civil servant from 1855 until his retirement in 1895.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1876, Alois was made legitimate and his baptismal record annotated by a priest to register Johann Georg Hiedler as Alois's father (recorded as "Georg Hitler").
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois then assumed the surname "Hitler", also spelled "Hiedler", "Hüttler", or "Huettler".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The name is probably based on the German word *Hütte* (lit.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] 'hut'), and has the meaning "one who lives in a hut".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi official Hans Frank suggested that Alois's mother had been employed as a housekeeper by a Jewish family in Graz, and that the family's 19-year-old son Leopold Frankenberger had fathered Alois, a claim that came to be known as the Frankenberger thesis.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] No Frankenberger was registered in Graz during that period, and no record has been produced of a Leopold Frankenberger's existence, so historians dismiss the claim that Alois's father was Jewish.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 2025, blood from the sofa in Hitler's study was used by Turi King of the University of Bath for DNA analysis.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The blood was confirmed to be Hitler's by comparing it to that of a male-line relative, and the DNA analysis also showed that Hitler did not have Jewish ancestry through his father.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] "If that was the case, we wouldn't have got the DNA match with him," King said.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Adolf Hitler was born on 20 April 1889 in Braunau am Inn, a town in Austria-Hungary (present-day Austria), close to the border with Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He was the fourth of six children born to Alois Hitler and his third wife, Klara Pölzl.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Three of Hitler's siblings—Gustav, Ida, and Otto—died in infancy.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Also living in the household were Alois's children from his second marriage: Alois Jr.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1892, the family moved to Passau, Germany, following Alois's promotion to the customs administration in Passau.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was promoted and transferred to Linz, Austria, on 1 April 1893, but the rest of the family remained in Passau.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] There, Hitler acquired the distinctive lower Bavarian dialect, rather than Austrian German, which marked his speech throughout his life.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The family returned to Austria and settled in Leonding on 9 May 1894, and in June 1895, Alois retired to Hafeld, near Lambach, where he farmed and kept bees.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler attended *Volksschule* (a state-funded primary school) in nearby Fischlham.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The move to Hafeld coincided with the onset of intense father–son conflicts caused by six-year-old Hitler's refusal to conform to the strict discipline of his school.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois tried to browbeat his son into obedience, while Adolf did his best to be the opposite of whatever his father wanted.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois would also beat his son, although his mother tried to protect him from regular beatings.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois Hitler's farming efforts at Hafeld were unsuccessful, and in 1897, the family moved to Lambach.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The eight-year-old Hitler took singing lessons, sang in the church choir, and even considered becoming a priest.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1898, the family returned permanently to Leonding.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was deeply affected by the death of his younger brother Edmund in 1900 from measles.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler transformed from a confident, outgoing, and conscientious student to a morose, detached boy who frequently clashed with his father and teachers.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Paula Hitler recalled that Adolf was a teenage bully who would often slap her.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois had made a successful career in the customs bureau and wanted his son to follow in his footsteps.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later dramatised an episode from this period when his father took him to visit a customs office, depicting it as an event that gave rise to an unforgiving antagonism between father and son, who were both strong-willed.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Ignoring his son's desire to attend a classical high school and become an artist, Alois sent Hitler to the *Realschule* in Linz in September 1900.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler rebelled against this decision, and in *Mein Kampf* states that he intentionally performed poorly in school, hoping that once his father saw "what little progress I was making at the technical school he would let me devote myself to my dream".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Like many Austrian Germans, Hitler began to develop German nationalist ideas from a young age.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He expressed loyalty only to Germany, despising the declining Habsburg monarchy and its rule over an ethnically diverse empire.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and his friends used the greeting "Heil", and sang the "Deutschlandlied" instead of the Austrian Imperial anthem.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] After Alois's sudden death on 3 January 1903, Hitler's performance at school deteriorated, and his mother allowed him to leave.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He enrolled at the *Realschule* in Steyr in September 1904, where his behaviour and performance improved.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1905, after passing a repeat of the final exam, Hitler left the school without any ambitions for further education or clear plans for a career.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1907, Hitler left Linz to live and study fine art in Vienna, financed by an orphan's benefits and support from his mother.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He applied for admission to the Academy of Fine Arts Vienna but was rejected twice.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The director suggested Hitler should apply to the School of Architecture, but he lacked the necessary academic credentials because he had not finished secondary school.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 December 1907, his mother died of breast cancer at the age of 47; Hitler was 18 at the time.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1909, Hitler ran out of money and was forced to live a bohemian life in homeless shelters and the Meldemannstraße dormitory.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He earned money as a casual labourer and by painting and selling watercolours of Vienna's sights.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] During his time in Vienna, he pursued a growing passion for architecture and music, attending ten performances of *Lohengrin*, his favourite of Richard Wagner's operas.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In Vienna, Hitler was first exposed to racist rhetoric.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Populists such as mayor Karl Lueger exploited the city's prevalent antisemitic sentiment, occasionally also espousing German nationalist notions for political benefit.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] German nationalism was especially widespread in the Mariahilf district, where Hitler then lived.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Georg Ritter von Schönerer became a major influence on Hitler, and he developed an admiration for Martin Luther.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler read newspapers and pamphlets that promoted prejudice and warned of an influx of Eastern European Jews, as well as writings by figures such as Houston Stewart Chamberlain, Charles Darwin, Friedrich Nietzsche, Gustave Le Bon, and Arthur Schopenhauer.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] During his years in Vienna he also developed strong anti-Slavic sentiments.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The origin and development of Hitler's antisemitism remain a matter of debate.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] His friend August Kubizek claimed that Hitler was a "confirmed antisemite" before he left Linz.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] However, the historian Brigitte Hamann describes Kubizek's claim as "problematical".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler states in *Mein Kampf* that he first became an antisemite in Vienna, Reinhold Hanisch, who helped him to sell his paintings, disagrees.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sold some of his art through a Jewish businessman named Samuel Morgenstern while living in Vienna.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of Morgenstern's clients were Jewish; for example, a lawyer named Josef Feingold purchased several of Hitler's paintings of Vienna's historical architecture.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Evans states that "historians now generally agree that his notorious, murderous antisemitism emerged well after Germany's defeat in World War I, as a product of the paranoid "stab-in-the-back" explanation for the catastrophe".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler received the final part of his father's estate in May 1913 and moved to Munich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] When he was conscripted into the Austro-Hungarian Army, he journeyed to Salzburg on 5 February 1914 for medical assessment.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] After he was deemed unfit for service, he returned to Munich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later claimed that he did not wish to serve the Habsburg Empire because of the mixture of races in its army and his belief that the collapse of Austria-Hungary was imminent.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Hitler was living in Munich and voluntarily enlisted in the Bavarian Army.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] According to a 1924 report by the Bavarian authorities, allowing Hitler to serve was most likely an administrative error, because as an Austrian citizen, he should have been returned to Austria.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Posted to the Bavarian Reserve Infantry Regiment 16 (1st Company of the List Regiment), he served as a dispatch runner on the Western Front in France and Belgium, spending nearly half his time at the regimental headquarters in Fournes-en-Weppes, well behind the front lines.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1914, he was present at the First Battle of Ypres and in that year was decorated for bravery, receiving the Iron Cross, Second Class.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] During the war, he was saved by his commanding officer, Fritz Wiedemann, who pulled Hitler out of the rubble of a collapsed building while under heavy fire.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] During his service at headquarters, Hitler pursued his artistic interests, drawing cartoons and providing instructions for an army newspaper.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] During the Battle of the Somme in October 1916, he was wounded in the left thigh when a shell exploded in the dispatch runners' dugout.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler spent almost two months recovering in hospital at Beelitz, returning to his regiment on 5 March 1917.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He was present at the Battle of Arras of 1917 and the Battle of Passchendaele.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He received the black Wound Badge on 18 May 1918.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Three months later, in August 1918, on a recommendation by Lieutenant Hugo Gutmann, his Jewish superior, Hitler received the Iron Cross, First Class, a decoration rarely awarded at Hitler's *Gefreiter* rank.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 15 October 1918, he was temporarily blinded in a mustard gas attack and was hospitalised in Pasewalk.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, Hitler learned of Germany's defeat, and, by his own account, suffered a second bout of blindness after receiving this news.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler described his role in World War I as "the greatest of all experiences" and was praised by his commanding officers for his bravery.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] His wartime experience reinforced his German patriotism, and he was shocked by Germany's capitulation in November 1918.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] His displeasure with the collapse of the war effort began to shape his ideology.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Treaty of Versailles stipulated that Germany had to relinquish several of its territories and demilitarise the Rhineland.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The treaty imposed economic sanctions and levied heavy reparations on the country.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Many Germans saw the treaty as an unjust humiliation.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] They especially objected to Article 231, which they interpreted as declaring Germany responsible for the war.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Versailles Treaty and the economic, social, and political conditions in Germany after the war were later exploited by Hitler for political gain.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] After the war, Hitler returned to Munich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Without formal education or career prospects, he remained in the army.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In July 1919, he was appointed *Verbindungsmann* (intelligence agent) of an *Aufklärungskommando* (reconnaissance unit) of the *Reichswehr*, assigned to influence other soldiers and to infiltrate the German Workers' Party (DAP).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] At a DAP meeting on 12 September 1919, Party chairman Anton Drexler was impressed by Hitler's oratorical skills.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He gave him a copy of his pamphlet *My Political Awakening*, which contained antisemitic, nationalist, anti-capitalist, and anti-Marxist ideas.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On the orders of his army superiors, Hitler applied to join the party, and within a week was accepted as party member 555 (the party began counting membership at 500 to give the impression they were a much larger party).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made his earliest known written statement about the Jewish question in a 16 September 1919 letter to Adolf Gemlich (now known as the Gemlich letter).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In the letter, Hitler argues that the aim of the government "must unshakably be the removal of the Jews altogether".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] At the DAP, Hitler met Dietrich Eckart, one of the party's founders and a member of the occult Thule Society.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Eckart became Hitler's mentor, exchanging ideas with him and introducing him to a wide range of Munich society.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] To increase its appeal, the DAP changed its name to the *Nationalsozialistische Deutsche Arbeiterpartei* (National Socialist German Workers' Party (NSDAP), now known as the "Nazi Party").
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler designed the party's banner of a swastika in a white circle on a red background.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was discharged from the army on 31 March 1920, and began working full-time for the party.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The party headquarters was in Munich, a centre for anti-government German nationalists determined to eliminate Marxism and undermine the Weimar Republic.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In February 1921, already highly effective at crowd manipulation, Hitler spoke to a crowd of over 6,000.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] To publicise the meeting, two truckloads of party supporters drove around Munich waving swastika flags and distributing leaflets.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler soon gained notoriety for his rowdy polemic speeches against the Treaty of Versailles, rival politicians, and especially against Marxists and Jews.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In June 1921, while Hitler and Eckart were on a fundraising trip to Berlin, a mutiny broke out within the Nazi Party in Munich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Members of its executive committee wanted to merge with the Nuremberg-based German Socialist Party (DSP).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler returned to Munich on 11 July and angrily tendered his resignation.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee members realised that the resignation of their leading public figure and speaker would mean the end of the party.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler announced he would rejoin on the condition that he would replace Drexler as party chairman, and that the party headquarters would remain in Munich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee agreed, and he rejoined the party on 26 July as member 3,680.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler continued to face some opposition within the Nazi Party.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Opponents of Hitler in the leadership had Hermann Esser expelled from the party, and they printed 3,000 copies of a pamphlet attacking Hitler as a traitor to the party.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In the following days, Hitler spoke to several large audiences and defended himself and Esser, to thunderous applause.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] His strategy proved successful, and at a special party congress on 29 July, he was granted absolute power as party chairman, succeeding Drexler, by a vote of 533 to 1.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's vitriolic beer hall speeches began attracting regular audiences.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] A demagogue, he became adept at using populist themes, including the use of scapegoats, who were blamed for his listeners' economic hardships.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used personal magnetism and an understanding of crowd psychology to his advantage while engaged in public speaking.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Historians have noted the hypnotic effect of his rhetoric on large audiences, and of his eyes in small groups.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Early followers included Rudolf Hess, the former air force ace Hermann Göring, and the army captain Ernst Röhm.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Röhm became head of the Nazis' paramilitary organisation, the *Sturmabteilung* (SA, "Stormtroopers"), which protected meetings and attacked political opponents.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] A critical influence on Hitler's thinking during this period was the *Aufbau Vereinigung*, a conspiratorial group of White Russian exiles and early Nazis.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The group, financed with funds channelled from wealthy industrialists, introduced Hitler to the idea of a Jewish conspiracy, linking international finance with Bolshevism.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The programme of the Nazi Party was laid out in their 25-point programme on 24 February 1920.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] This did not represent a coherent ideology, but was a conglomeration of received ideas which had currency in the *völkisch* pan-Germanic movement, such as ultranationalism, opposition to the Treaty of Versailles, distrust of capitalism, as well as some socialist ideas.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] For Hitler, the most important aspect of it was its strong antisemitic stance.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He also perceived the programme as primarily a basis for propaganda and for attracting people to the party.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, Hitler enlisted the help of World War I General Erich Ludendorff for an attempted coup known as the Beer Hall Putsch.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party used Italian Fascism as a model for their appearance and policies.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler wanted to emulate Benito Mussolini's March on Rome in 1922 by staging his own coup in Bavaria, to be followed by a challenge to the government in Berlin.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and Ludendorff sought the support of *Staatskommissar* (State Commissioner) Gustav Ritter von Kahr, Bavaria's *de facto* ruler.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] However, Kahr, along with Police Chief Hans Ritter von Seisser and Reichswehr General Otto von Lossow, wanted to install a nationalist dictatorship without Hitler.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 8 November 1923, Hitler and the SA stormed a public meeting of 3,000 people organised by Kahr in the Bürgerbräukeller, a beer hall in Munich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Interrupting Kahr's speech, he announced that the national revolution had begun and declared the formation of a new government with Ludendorff.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Retiring to a back room, Hitler, with his pistol drawn, demanded and subsequently received the support of Kahr, Seisser, and Lossow.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's forces initially succeeded in occupying the local Reichswehr and police headquarters, but Kahr and his cohorts quickly withdrew their support.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Neither the Army nor the state police joined forces with Hitler.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The next day, Hitler and his followers marched from the beer hall to the Bavarian War Ministry to overthrow the Bavarian government, but police dispersed them.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In the failed coup, 16 Nazi Party members and four police officers were killed.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler fled to the home of Ernst Hanfstaengl and by some accounts contemplated suicide.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He was depressed but calm when arrested on 11 November 1923 for high treason.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] His trial before the special People's Court in Munich began in February 1924, and Alfred Rosenberg became the temporary leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 April, Hitler was sentenced to five years' *Festungshaft* ('fortress confinement') at Landsberg Prison.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] There, he received friendly treatment from the guards and was allowed mail from supporters and regular visits by party comrades.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Pardoned by the Bavarian Supreme Court, he was released from jail on 20 December 1924, against the state prosecutor's objections.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Including time on remand, Hitler served just over one year in prison.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] While at Landsberg, Hitler dictated most of the first volume of *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] 'My Struggle'; originally titled *Four and a Half Years of Struggle against Lies, Stupidity, and Cowardice*) at first to his chauffeur, Emil Maurice, and then to his deputy, Rudolf Hess.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The book, dedicated to Thule Society member Dietrich Eckart, was an autobiography and exposition of his ideology.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The book laid out Hitler's plans for territorial expansion as well as transforming German society into a dictatorship based on race.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Throughout the book, Jews are equated with "germs" and presented as the "international poisoners" of society.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] According to Hitler's ideology, the only solution was their extermination.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler did not describe exactly how this was to be accomplished, his "inherent genocidal thrust is undeniable", according to Ian Kershaw.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Published in two volumes in 1925 and 1926, *Mein Kampf* sold 228,000 copies between 1925 and 1932.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] One million copies were sold in 1933, Hitler's first year in office.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly before Hitler was eligible for parole, the Bavarian government attempted to have him deported to Austria.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Austrian federal chancellor rejected the request on the specious grounds that his service in the German Army made his Austrian citizenship void.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler formally renounced his Austrian citizenship on 7 April 1925.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] At the time of Hitler's release from prison, politics in Germany had become less combative, and the economy had improved, limiting Hitler's opportunities for political agitation.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] As a result of the failed Beer Hall Putsch, the Nazi Party and its affiliated organisations were banned in Bavaria.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with the prime minister of Bavaria, Heinrich Held, on 4 January 1925, Hitler agreed to respect the state's authority and promised that he would seek political power only through the democratic process.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The meeting paved the way for the ban on the Nazi Party to be lifted on 16 February.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] However, after an inflammatory speech he gave on 27 February, Hitler was barred from public speaking by the Bavarian authorities, a ban that remained in place until 1927.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] To advance his political ambitions despite the ban, Hitler appointed Gregor Strasser, Otto Strasser, and Joseph Goebbels to organise and enlarge the Nazi Party in northern Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Gregor Strasser steered a more independent political course, emphasising the socialist elements of the party's programme.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The stock market in the United States crashed on 24 October 1929.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The impact in Germany was dire: millions became unemployed, and several major banks collapsed.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazi Party prepared to take advantage of the emergency to gain support for their party.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] They promised to repudiate the Versailles Treaty, strengthen the economy, and provide jobs.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Great Depression provided a political opportunity for Hitler.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Germans were ambivalent about the parliamentary republic, which faced challenges from right- and left-wing extremists.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The moderate political parties were increasingly unable to stem the tide of extremism, and the German referendum of 1929 helped to elevate Nazi ideology.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The elections of September 1930 resulted in the break-up of a grand coalition and its replacement with a minority cabinet.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Its leader, chancellor Heinrich Brüning of the Centre Party, governed through emergency decrees from President Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Governance by decree became the new norm, paving the way for authoritarian forms of government.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party rose from obscurity to win 18.3 per cent of the vote and 107 parliamentary seats in the 1930 election, becoming the second-largest party in parliament.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made a prominent appearance at the trial of two Reichswehr officers, Lieutenants Richard Scheringer and Hanns Ludin, in late 1930.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Both were charged with membership in the Nazi Party, at that time illegal for Reichswehr personnel.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The prosecution argued that the Nazi Party was extremist, prompting defence lawyer Hans Frank to call on Hitler to testify.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 September 1930, Hitler testified that his party would pursue political power solely through democratic elections, which won him many supporters in the officer corps.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Brüning's austerity measures brought little economic improvement and were extremely unpopular.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler exploited this by targeting his political messages specifically at people who had been affected by the inflation of the 1920s and the Depression, such as farmers, war veterans, and the middle class.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Although Hitler had terminated his Austrian citizenship in 1925, he did not acquire German citizenship for almost seven years.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] This meant that he was stateless, legally unable to run for public office, and still faced the risk of deportation.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 February 1932, the interior minister of Brunswick, Dietrich Klagges, who was a member of the Nazi Party, appointed Hitler as administrator for the state's delegation to the Reichsrat in Berlin, making Hitler a citizen of Brunswick, and thus of Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler ran against Hindenburg in the 1932 presidential election.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] A speech to the Industry Club in Düsseldorf on 27 January 1932 won him support from many of Germany's most powerful industrialists.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg had support from various nationalist, monarchist, Catholic, and republican parties, and some Social Democrats.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used the campaign slogan "*Hitler über Deutschland*" ("Hitler over Germany"), a reference to his political ambitions and his campaigning by aircraft.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He was one of the first politicians to use aircraft travel for campaigning and used it effectively.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler came in second in both rounds of the election, garnering more than 35 per cent of the vote in the final election.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Although he lost to Hindenburg, this election established Hitler as a strong force in German politics.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The absence of an effective government prompted two influential politicians, Franz von Papen and Alfred Hugenberg, along with several other industrialists and businessmen, to write a letter to Hindenburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The signers urged Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as leader of a government "independent from parliamentary parties", which could turn into a movement that would "enrapture millions of people".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg reluctantly agreed to appoint Hitler as chancellor after two further parliamentary elections—in July and November 1932—had not resulted in the formation of a majority government.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler headed a short-lived coalition government formed by the Nazi Party (which had the most seats in the Reichstag) and Hugenberg's party, the German National People's Party (DNVP).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 30 January 1933, the new cabinet was sworn in during a brief ceremony in Hindenburg's office.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party gained three posts: Hitler was named chancellor, Wilhelm Frick Minister of the Interior, and Hermann Göring Minister of the Interior for Prussia.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler had insisted on the ministerial positions as a way to gain control over the police in much of Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] As chancellor, Hitler worked against attempts by the Nazi Party's opponents to build a majority government.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Because of the political stalemate, he asked Hindenburg to again dissolve the Reichstag, and elections were scheduled for early March.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 27 February 1933, the Reichstag building was set on fire.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Göring blamed a communist plot, as the Dutch communist Marinus van der Lubbe was found in incriminating circumstances inside the burning building.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Until the 1960s, some historians, including William L.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Shirer and Alan Bullock, thought the Nazi Party was responsible; now the view of most historians is van der Lubbe started the fire alone.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] At Hitler's urging, Hindenburg responded by signing the Reichstag Fire Decree of 28 February, drafted by the Nazis, which suspended basic rights and allowed detention without trial.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The decree was permitted under Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution, which gave the president the power to take emergency measures to protect public safety and order.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Activities of the German Communist Party (KPD) were suppressed, and 4,000 KPD members were arrested.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition to political campaigning, the Nazi Party engaged in paramilitary violence and the spread of anti-communist propaganda, in the days preceding the election.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On election day, 6 March 1933, the Nazis’ share of the vote increased to 44%, and the party acquired the largest number of seats in parliament.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's party failed to secure an absolute majority, necessitating another coalition with the DNVP.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 March 1933, the new *Reichstag* was constituted with an opening ceremony at the Garrison Church in Potsdam.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] This "Day of Potsdam" was held to demonstrate unity between the Nazi movement and the old Prussian elite and military.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler appeared in a morning coat and humbly greeted Hindenburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] To achieve full political control despite not having an absolute majority in parliament, Hitler's government brought the *Ermächtigungsgesetz* (Enabling Act) to a vote in the newly elected *Reichstag*.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act—officially titled the *Gesetz zur Behebung der Not von Volk und Reich* ("Law to Remedy the Distress of People and Reich")—gave Hitler's cabinet the power to enact laws without the consent of the Reichstag for four years.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] These laws could (with certain exceptions) deviate from the constitution.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Since it would affect the constitution, the Enabling Act required a two-thirds majority to pass.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Leaving nothing to chance, the Nazis used the provisions of the Reichstag Fire Decree to arrest all 81 Communist deputies (in spite of their virulent campaign against the party, the Nazis had allowed the KPD to contest the election) and prevent several Social Democrats from attending.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 23 March 1933, the *Reichstag* assembled at the Kroll Opera House under turbulent circumstances.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Ranks of SA men served as guards inside the building, while large groups outside, opposing the proposed legislation, shouted slogans and threats towards the arriving members of parliament.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] After Hitler verbally promised Centre party leader Ludwig Kaas that Hindenburg would retain his power of veto, Kaas announced the Centre Party would support the Enabling Act.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act was passed by a vote of 444–94, with all parties except the Social Democrats voting in favour.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Enabling Act, along with the Reichstag Fire Decree, transformed Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Having achieved full control over the legislative and executive branches of government, Hitler and his allies began to suppress the remaining opposition.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Social Democratic Party was made illegal, and its assets were seized.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] While many trade union delegates were in Berlin for May Day activities, SA stormtroopers occupied union offices around the country.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 2 May 1933, all trade unions were forced to dissolve, and their leaders were arrested.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The German Labour Front was formed as an umbrella organisation to represent all workers, administrators, and company owners, thus reflecting the concept of Nazism in the spirit of Hitler's *Volksgemeinschaft* ("people's community").
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of June, the other parties had been intimidated into disbanding.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] This included the Nazis' nominal coalition partner, the DNVP; with the SA's help, Hitler forced its leader, Hugenberg, to resign on 29 June.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 14 July 1933, the Nazi Party was declared the only legal political party in Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The demands of the SA for more political and military power caused anxiety among military, industrial, and political leaders.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler purged the entire SA leadership in the Night of the Long Knives, which took place from 30 June to 2 July 1934.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler targeted Ernst Röhm and other SA leaders who, along with several Hitler's political adversaries (such as Gregor Strasser and former chancellor Kurt von Schleicher), were rounded up, arrested, and shot.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] While the international community and some Germans were shocked by the killings, many in Germany believed Hitler was restoring order.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On the previous day, the cabinet had enacted the Law Concerning the Head of State of the German Reich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] This law stated that upon Hindenburg's death, the office of president would be abolished, and its powers merged with those of the chancellor.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler thus became head of state as well as head of government and was formally named as *Führer und Reichskanzler* (Leader and Chancellor of the Reich), although *Reichskanzler* was eventually dropped.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] With this action, Hitler eliminated the last legal remedy by which he could be removed from office.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] As head of state, Hitler became commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 19 August, the merger of the presidency with the chancellorship was approved by 88 per cent of the electorate voting in a plebiscite.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, Hitler used blackmail to consolidate his hold over the military by instigating the Blomberg–Fritsch affair.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler forced his War Minister, Field Marshal Werner von Blomberg, to resign by using a police dossier that showed that Blomberg's new wife had a record for prostitution.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Army commander Colonel-General Werner von Fritsch was removed after the *Schutzstaffel* (SS) produced allegations that he had engaged in a homosexual relationship.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Both men had fallen into disfavour because they objected to Hitler's demand to make the *Wehrmacht* ready for war as early as 1938.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler assumed Blomberg's title of Commander-in-Chief, thus taking personal command of the armed forces.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He replaced the Ministry of War with the *Oberkommando der Wehrmacht* (OKW), headed by General Wilhelm Keitel.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On the same day, 16 generals were stripped of their commands, and 44 more were transferred; all were suspected of not being sufficiently pro-Nazi.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] By early February 1938, 12 more generals had been removed.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler took care to give his dictatorship the appearance of legality.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of his decrees were explicitly based on the Reichstag Fire Decree and hence on Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The *Reichstag* renewed the Enabling Act twice, each time for four years.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] While elections to the *Reichstag* were still held (in 1933, 1936, and 1938), voters were presented with a single list of Nazis and pro-Nazi "guests" which received well over 90 per cent of the vote.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] These sham elections were held in far-from-secret conditions; the Nazis threatened severe reprisals against anyone who did not vote or who voted against.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1934, Hitler appointed *Reichsbank* President Hjalmar Schacht as Minister of Economics, and in the following year, as Plenipotentiary for War Economy in charge of preparing the economy for war.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Reconstruction and rearmament were financed through Mefo bills, printing money, and seizing the assets of people arrested as enemies of the state, including Jews.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of unemployed fell from six million in 1932 to fewer than one million in 1936.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler oversaw one of the largest infrastructure improvement campaigns in German history, leading to the construction of dams, *autobahns*, railroads, and other civil works.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Wages were slightly lower in the mid- to late 1930s compared with wages during the Weimar Republic, while the cost of living increased by 25 per cent.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The average workweek increased during the shift to a war economy; by 1939, the average German was working between 47 and 50 hours a week.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's government sponsored architecture on an immense scale.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Albert Speer, instrumental in implementing Hitler's classicist reinterpretation of German culture, was placed in charge of the proposed architectural renovations of Berlin.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Despite a threatened multi-nation boycott, Germany hosted the 1936 Olympic Games.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler officiated at the opening ceremonies and attended events at both the Winter Games in Garmisch-Partenkirchen and the Summer Games in Berlin.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with German military leaders on 3 February 1933, Hitler spoke of "conquest for *Lebensraum* in the East and its ruthless Germanisation" as his ultimate foreign policy objectives.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler found Bülow's goals to be too modest.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In speeches during this period, he stressed what he termed the peaceful goals of his policies and a willingness to work within international agreements.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] At the first meeting of his cabinet in 1933, Hitler prioritised military spending over unemployment relief.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany withdrew from the League of Nations and the World Disarmament Conference in October 1933.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In January 1935, over 90 per cent of the people of the Saarland, then under League of Nations administration, voted to unite with Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] That March, Hitler announced an expansion of the Wehrmacht to 600,000 members—six times the number permitted by the Versailles Treaty—including development of an air force (*Luftwaffe*) and an increase in the size of the navy (*Kriegsmarine*).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, France, Italy, and the League of Nations condemned these violations of the Treaty but did nothing to stop them.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The Anglo-German Naval Agreement (AGNA) of 18 June allowed German tonnage to increase to 35 per cent of that of the Royal Navy.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler called the signing of the AGNA "the happiest day of his life", believing that the agreement marked the beginning of the Anglo-German alliance he had predicted in *Mein Kampf*.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] France and Italy were not consulted before the signing, directly undermining the League of Nations and setting the Treaty of Versailles on the path towards irrelevance.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany reoccupied the demilitarised zone in the Rhineland in March 1936, in violation of the Versailles Treaty.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sent troops to Spain to support Francisco Franco and his Nationalist faction during the Spanish Civil War after receiving an appeal for help in July 1936.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] At the same time, Hitler continued his efforts to create an Anglo-German alliance.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1936, in response to a growing economic crisis caused by his rearmament efforts, Hitler ordered Göring to implement a Four Year Plan to prepare Germany for war within the next four years.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] The plan envisaged an all-out struggle between "Judaeo-Bolshevism" and German Nazism, which in Hitler's view required a committed effort of rearmament regardless of the economic costs.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In October 1936, Count Galeazzo Ciano, foreign minister of Mussolini's government, visited Germany, where he signed a Nine-Point Protocol as an expression of *rapprochement* and had a personal meeting with Hitler.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 November, Mussolini declared an "axis" between Germany and Italy.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 November, Germany signed the Anti-Comintern Pact with Japan.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, China, Italy, and Poland were also invited to join the Anti-Comintern Pact, but only Italy signed in 1937.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler abandoned his plan of an Anglo-German alliance, blaming "inadequate" British leadership.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] At a meeting in the Reich Chancellery with his foreign ministers and military chiefs that November, Hitler restated his intention of acquiring *Lebensraum* for the German people.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He ordered preparations for war in the East to begin as early as 1938 and no later than 1943.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In the event of his death, the conference minutes, recorded as the Hossbach Memorandum, were to be regarded as his "political testament".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] He felt that a severe decline in living standards in Germany as a result of the economic crisis could only be stopped by military aggression aimed at seizing Austria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler urged quick action before Britain and France gained a permanent lead in the arms race.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, in the wake of the Blomberg–Fritsch affair, Hitler asserted control of the military-foreign policy apparatus, dismissing Neurath as foreign minister and appointing himself as War Minister.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p01] From early 1938 onwards, Hitler was carrying out a foreign policy ultimately aimed at war.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In February 1938, on the advice of his newly appointed foreign minister, the strongly pro-Japanese Joachim von Ribbentrop, Hitler ended the Sino-German alliance with the Republic of China to instead enter into an alliance with the more modern and powerful Empire of Japan.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler announced German recognition of Manchukuo, the Japanese puppet state in Manchuria, and renounced German claims to their former colonies in the Pacific held by Japan.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered an end to arms shipments to China and recalled all German officers working with the Chinese Army.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In retaliation, Chinese General Chiang Kai-shek cancelled all Sino-German economic agreements, depriving the Germans of many Chinese raw materials.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 March 1938, Hitler announced the unification of Austria with Germany in the *Anschluss*.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler then turned his attention to the ethnic German population of the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28–29 March 1938, Hitler held a series of secret meetings in Berlin with Konrad Henlein of the Sudeten German Party, the largest of the ethnic German parties of the Sudetenland.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The men agreed that Henlein would demand increased autonomy for Sudeten Germans from the Czechoslovak government, thus providing a pretext for German military action against Czechoslovakia.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In April 1938, Henlein told the foreign minister of Hungary that "whatever the Czech government might offer, he would always raise still higher demands ... he wanted to sabotage an understanding by any means because this was the only method to blow up Czechoslovakia quickly".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In private, Hitler considered the Sudeten issue unimportant; his real intention was a war of conquest against Czechoslovakia.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler ordered the OKW to prepare for *Fall Grün* (Case Green), the code name for an invasion of Czechoslovakia.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of intense French and British diplomatic pressure, on 5 September, Czechoslovak president Edvard Beneš unveiled the "Fourth Plan" for constitutional reorganisation of his country, which agreed to most of Henlein's demands for Sudeten autonomy.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Henlein's party responded to Beneš's offer by instigating a series of violent clashes with the Czechoslovak police that led to the declaration of martial law in certain Sudeten districts.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany was dependent on imported oil; a confrontation with Britain over the Czechoslovak dispute could curtail Germany's oil supplies.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] This forced Hitler to call off *Fall Grün*, originally planned for 1 October 1938.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 29 September, Hitler, Neville Chamberlain, Édouard Daladier, and Mussolini attended a one-day conference in Munich that led to the Munich Agreement, which handed over the Sudetenland districts to Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Chamberlain was satisfied with the Munich conference, calling the outcome "peace for our time", while Hitler was angered about the missed opportunity for war in 1938; he expressed his disappointment in a speech on 9 October in Saarbrücken.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In Hitler's view, the British-brokered peace, although favourable to the ostensible German demands, was a diplomatic defeat which spurred his intent of limiting British power to pave the way for the eastern expansion of Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of the summit, Hitler was selected *Time* magazine's Man of the Year for 1938.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1938 and early 1939, the continuing economic crisis caused by rearmament forced Hitler to make major defence cuts.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In his "Export or die" speech of 30 January 1939, he called for an economic offensive to increase German foreign exchange holdings to pay for raw materials such as high-grade iron needed for military weapons.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 14 March 1939, under threat from Hungary, Slovakia declared independence and received protection from Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The next day, in violation of the Munich Agreement and possibly as a result of the deepening economic crisis requiring additional assets, Hitler ordered the Wehrmacht to invade the Czech rump state, and from Prague Castle he proclaimed the territory a German protectorate.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In private discussions in 1939, Hitler declared Britain the main enemy to be defeated and that Poland's obliteration was a necessary prelude for that goal.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The eastern flank would be secured, and land would be added to Germany's *Lebensraum*.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Offended by the British "guarantee" on 31 March 1939 of Polish independence, he said, "I shall brew them a devil's drink".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In a speech in Wilhelmshaven for the launch of the battleship *Tirpitz* on 1 April, he threatened to denounce the Anglo-German Naval Agreement if the British continued to guarantee Polish independence, which he perceived as an "encirclement" policy.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Poland was to either become a German satellite state, or it would be neutralised to secure the Reich's eastern flank and prevent a possible British blockade.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler initially favoured the idea of a satellite state, but upon its rejection by the Polish government, he decided to invade and made this the main foreign policy goal of 1939.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 3 April, Hitler ordered the military to prepare for *Fall Weiss* ("Case White"), the plan for invading Poland on 25 August.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In a Reichstag speech on 28 April, he renounced both the Anglo-German Naval Agreement and the German–Polish Non-Aggression Pact.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians such as William Carr, Gerhard Weinberg, and Ian Kershaw have argued that one reason for Hitler's rush to war was his fear of an early death.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He had repeatedly claimed that he must lead Germany into war before he got too old, as his successors might lack his strength of will.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was concerned that a military attack against Poland could result in a premature war with Britain.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's foreign minister and former Ambassador to London, Joachim von Ribbentrop, assured him that neither Britain nor France would honour its commitments to Poland.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Accordingly, on 22 August 1939, Hitler ordered a military mobilisation against Poland.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] This plan required tacit Soviet support, and the non-aggression pact (the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact) between Germany and the Soviet Union, led by Joseph Stalin, included a secret agreement to partition Poland between the two countries.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Contrary to Ribbentrop's prediction that Britain would sever Anglo-Polish ties, Britain and Poland signed the Anglo-Polish alliance on 25 August 1939.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] This, along with news from Italy that Mussolini would not honour the Pact of Steel, prompted Hitler to postpone the attack on Poland from 25 August to 1 September.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler unsuccessfully tried to manoeuvre the British into neutrality by offering them a non-aggression guarantee on 25 August; he then instructed Ribbentrop to present a last-minute peace plan with an impossibly short time limit in an effort to blame the imminent war on British and Polish inaction.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 1 September 1939, Germany invaded western Poland under the pretext of having been denied claims to the Free City of Danzig and the right to extraterritorial roads across the Polish Corridor, which Germany had ceded under the Versailles Treaty.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In response, Britain and France declared war on Germany on 3 September, surprising Hitler and prompting him to angrily ask Ribbentrop, "Now what?" Britain and France did not act on their declarations immediately, and on 17 September, Soviet forces invaded eastern Poland.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The fall of Poland was followed by what contemporary journalists dubbed the "Phoney War" or *Sitzkrieg* ("sitting war").
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler instructed the two newly appointed Gauleiters of north-western Poland, Albert Forster of Reichsgau Danzig-West Prussia and Arthur Greiser of Reichsgau Wartheland, to Germanise their areas, with "no questions asked" about how this was accomplished.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In Forster's area, ethnic Poles merely had to sign forms stating that they had German blood.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In contrast, Greiser agreed with Himmler and carried out an ethnic cleansing campaign towards Poles.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Greiser soon complained that Forster was allowing thousands of Poles to be accepted as "racial" Germans and thus endangered German "racial purity".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] This inaction has been cited as an example of the theory of "working towards the Führer", in which Hitler issued vague instructions and expected his subordinates to develop policies independently.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Another dispute pitched one side represented by Heinrich Himmler and Greiser, who championed ethnic cleansing in Poland, against another represented by Göring and Hans Frank (governor-general of occupied Poland), who called for turning Poland into the "granary" of the Reich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 February 1940, the dispute was initially settled in favour of the Göring–Frank view, which ended the economically disruptive mass expulsions.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 May 1940, Himmler issued a memo entitled "Some Thoughts on the Treatment of Alien Population in the East", calling for the expulsion of the entire Jewish population of Europe into Africa and the reduction of the Polish population to a "leaderless class of labourers".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler called Himmler's memo "good and correct", and, ignoring Göring and Frank, implemented the Himmler–Greiser policy in Poland.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 9 April, German forces invaded Denmark and Norway.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On the same day, Hitler proclaimed the birth of the Greater Germanic Reich, his vision of a united empire of Germanic nations of Europe in which the Dutch, Flemish, and Scandinavians were joined into a "racially pure" polity under German leadership.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In May 1940, Germany attacked France, and conquered Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] These victories prompted Mussolini to have Italy join forces with Hitler on 10 June.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] France and Germany signed an armistice on 22 June.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw notes that Hitler's popularity within Germany—and German support for the war—reached its peak when he returned to Berlin on 6 July from his tour of Paris.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the unexpected swift victory, Hitler promoted 12 generals to the rank of field marshal during the 1940 Field Marshal Ceremony.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Britain, whose troops were forced to evacuate France by sea from Dunkirk, continued to fight alongside other British dominions in the Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler made peace overtures to the new British prime minister, Winston Churchill, and upon their rejection, he ordered a series of aerial attacks on Royal Air Force airbases and radar stations in southeast England.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 September, the systematic nightly bombing of London began.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The German Luftwaffe failed to defeat the Royal Air Force in what became known as the Battle of Britain.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] By the end of September, Hitler realised that air superiority for the invasion of Britain (in Operation Sea Lion) could not be achieved, and ordered the operation postponed.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The nightly air raids on British cities intensified and continued for months, including London, Plymouth, and Coventry.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 27 September 1940, the Tripartite Pact was signed in Berlin by Saburō Kurusu of Imperial Japan, Hitler, and Italian foreign minister Ciano, and later expanded to include Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria, thus yielding the Axis powers.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's attempt to integrate the Soviet Union into the anti-British bloc failed after inconclusive talks between Hitler and Molotov in Berlin in November, and he ordered preparations for the invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In early 1941, German forces were deployed to North Africa, the Balkans, and the Middle East.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In February, German forces arrived in Libya to bolster the Italian presence.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler launched the invasion of Yugoslavia, quickly followed by the invasion of Greece.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In May, German forces were sent to support Iraqi forces fighting against the British and to invade Crete.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 November, Hitler met in Berlin with Amin al-Husseini, the Grand Mufti of Jerusalem.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 June 1941, contravening the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact of 1939, over three million Axis troops attacked the Soviet Union.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] This offensive (codenamed Operation Barbarossa) was intended to destroy the Soviet Union and seize its natural resources for subsequent aggression against the Western powers.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The action was also part of the overall plan to obtain more living space for German people; and Hitler thought a successful invasion would force Britain to negotiate a surrender.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The invasion conquered a huge area, including the Baltic republics, Belarus, and West Ukraine.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] By early August, Axis troops had advanced 500 km (310 miles) and won the Battle of Smolensk.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Army Group Centre to temporarily halt its advance to Moscow and divert its Panzer groups to aid in the encirclement of Leningrad and Kiev.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] His generals disagreed with this change, having advanced within 400 km (250 miles) of Moscow, and his decision caused a crisis among the military leadership.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The pause provided the Red Army with an opportunity to mobilise fresh reserves; the historian Russel Stolfi considers it to be one of the major factors that caused the failure of the Moscow offensive, which was resumed in October 1941 and ended disastrously in December.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] During this crisis, Hitler appointed himself as head of the *Oberkommando des Heeres*.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 December 1941, Japan attacked the American fleet based at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Four days later, Hitler declared war against the United States.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 18 December 1941, Himmler asked Hitler, "What to do with the Jews of Russia?", to which Hitler replied, *"als Partisanen auszurotten"* ("exterminate them as partisans").
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The Israeli historian Yehuda Bauer has commented that the remark is probably as close as historians will ever get to a definitive order from Hitler for the genocide carried out during the Holocaust.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1942, German forces were defeated in the Second Battle of El Alamein, thwarting Hitler's plans to seize the Suez Canal and the Middle East.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Overconfident in his own military expertise following the earlier victories in 1940, Hitler became distrustful of his Army High Command and began to interfere in military and tactical planning, with damaging consequences.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In December 1942 and January 1943, Hitler's repeated refusal to allow their withdrawal at the Battle of Stalingrad led to the near-destruction of the 6th Army.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Over 200,000 Axis soldiers were killed, and 235,000 were taken prisoner.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Thereafter came a decisive strategic defeat at the Battle of Kursk.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's military judgment became increasingly erratic, and Germany's military and economic position deteriorated, as did Hitler's health.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the Allied invasion of Sicily in 1943, Mussolini was removed from power by King Victor Emmanuel III after a vote of no confidence of the Grand Council of Fascism.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Marshal Pietro Badoglio, placed in charge of the government, soon surrendered to the Allies.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Throughout 1943 and 1944, the Soviet Union steadily forced Hitler's armies into retreat along the Eastern Front.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 6 June 1944, the Western Allied armies landed in northern France in one of the largest amphibious operations in history, Operation Overlord.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Many German officers concluded that defeat was inevitable and that continuing under Hitler's leadership would result in the complete destruction of the country.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Between 1939 and 1945, there were numerous plans to assassinate Hitler, some of which proceeded to significant degrees.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The most well-known and significant, the 20 July plot of 1944, came from within Germany and was at least partly driven by the increasing prospect of a German defeat in the war.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Part of Operation Valkyrie, the plot involved Claus von Stauffenberg planting a bomb in one of Hitler's headquarters, the Wolf's Lair at Rastenburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler narrowly survived because the staff officer Heinz Brandt moved the briefcase containing the bomb behind a leg of the heavy conference table, which deflected much of the blast.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Later, Hitler ordered reprisals, resulting in the execution of more than 4,900 people.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was put on the United Nations War Crimes Commission's first list of war criminals in December 1944, after determining that Hitler could be held criminally responsible for the acts of the Nazis in occupied countries.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] By March 1945, at least seven indictments had been filed against him.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] By late 1944, both the Red Army and the Western Allies were advancing into Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Recognising the strength and determination of the Red Army, Hitler decided to use his remaining mobile reserves against the American and British armies, which he perceived as far weaker.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 16 December, he launched the Ardennes Offensive to incite disunity among the Western Allies and perhaps convince them to join his fight against the Soviets.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] After some temporary successes, the offensive failed.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In any case only those who are inferior will remain after this struggle, for the good have already been killed".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The same day, Hitler ordered the destruction of all German industrial infrastructure before it could fall into Allied hands.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Minister for Armaments Albert Speer was entrusted with executing this scorched earth policy, but he secretly disobeyed the order.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's hope to negotiate peace with the United States and Britain was encouraged by the death of US president Franklin D.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Roosevelt on 12 April 1945, but contrary to his expectations, this caused no rift among the Allies.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 20 April, his 56th birthday, Hitler made his last trip from the *Führerbunker* to the surface.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In the ruined garden of the Reich Chancellery, he awarded Iron Crosses to boy soldiers of the Hitler Youth, who were now fighting the Red Army at the front near Berlin.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] By 21 April, Georgy Zhukov's 1st Belorussian Front had broken through the defences of General Gotthard Heinrici's Army Group Vistula during the Battle of the Seelow Heights and advanced to the outskirts of Berlin.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In denial about the dire situation, Hitler placed his hopes on the undermanned and under-equipped *Armeeabteilung Steiner* (Army Detachment Steiner), commanded by Felix Steiner.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Steiner to attack the northern flank of the salient, while the German Ninth Army was ordered to attack northward in a pincer attack.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] During a military conference on 22 April, Hitler enquired about Steiner's offensive.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He was informed that the attack had not been launched and that the Soviets had entered Berlin.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered everyone but Wilhelm Keitel, Alfred Jodl, Hans Krebs, and Wilhelm Burgdorf to leave the room, then launched into a tirade against the perceived treachery and incompetence of his generals, culminating in his declaration—for the first time—that "everything is lost".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He announced that he would stay in Berlin until the end and then shoot himself.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] By 23 April, the Red Army had surrounded Berlin, and Goebbels made a proclamation urging its citizens to defend the city.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] That same day, Göring sent a telegram from Berchtesgaden, arguing that as Hitler was isolated in Berlin, Göring should assume leadership of Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Göring set a deadline, after which he would consider Hitler incapacitated.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler responded by having Göring arrested, and in his last will and testament of 29 April, he removed Göring from all government positions.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 April, Hitler discovered that Himmler, who had left Berlin on 20 April, was attempting to negotiate a surrender to the Western Allies.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He considered this treason and ordered Himmler's arrest.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He also ordered the execution of Hermann Fegelein, Himmler's SS representative at Hitler's headquarters in Berlin, for desertion.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] After midnight on the night of 28–29 April, Hitler married Eva Braun in a small civil ceremony in the *Führerbunker*.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Later that afternoon, Hitler was informed that Mussolini had been executed by the Italian resistance movement on the previous day; this is believed to have increased his determination to avoid capture.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 30 April, Soviet troops were within five hundred metres of the Reich Chancellery when Hitler shot himself in the head and Braun bit into a cyanide capsule.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In accordance with Hitler's wishes, their corpses were carried outside to the garden behind the Reich Chancellery, where they were placed in a bomb crater, doused with petrol, and set on fire as the Red Army shelling continued.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Grand Admiral Karl Dönitz and Goebbels assumed Hitler's roles as head of state and chancellor respectively.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On the evening of 1 May, Goebbels and his wife, Magda, committed suicide in the Reich Chancellery garden, after having poisoned their six children with cyanide.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The remains of the Goebbels family, General Hans Krebs (who had committed suicide that day), and Hitler's dog Blondi were repeatedly buried and exhumed by the Soviets.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's and Braun's remains were alleged to have been moved as well, but this is most likely Soviet disinformation.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] There is no evidence that any identifiable remains of Hitler or Braun—with the exception of dental bridges—were ever found by them.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] While news of Hitler's death spread quickly, a death certificate was not issued until 1956, after a lengthy investigation to collect testimony from 42 witnesses.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's death was entered as an assumption of death based on this testimony.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The Holocaust and Germany's war in the East were based on Hitler's long-standing view that the Jews were the enemy of the German people, and that *Lebensraum* was needed for Germany's expansion.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He focused on Eastern Europe for this expansion, aiming to defeat Poland and the Soviet Union and then removing or killing the Jews and Slavs.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The *Generalplan Ost* (General Plan East) called for deporting the population of occupied Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union to West Siberia, for use as slave labour or to be murdered; the conquered territories were to be colonised by German or "Germanised" settlers.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The goal was to implement this plan after the conquest of the Soviet Union, but when this failed, Hitler moved the plans forward.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] By January 1942, he had decided that the Jews, Slavs, and other deportees considered undesirable should be killed.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The genocide was organised and executed by Heinrich Himmler and Reinhard Heydrich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The records of the Wannsee Conference, held on 20 January 1942 and led by Heydrich, with 15 senior Nazi officials participating, provide the clearest evidence of systematic planning for the Holocaust.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 February, Hitler was recorded saying, "we shall regain our health only by eliminating the Jews".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Similarly, at a meeting in July 1941 with leading functionaries of the Eastern territories, Hitler said that the easiest way to quickly pacify the areas would be best achieved by "shooting everyone who even looks odd".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Although no direct order from Hitler authorising the mass killings has surfaced, his public speeches, orders to his generals, and the diaries of Nazi officials demonstrate that he conceived and authorised the extermination of European Jewry.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] During the war, Hitler repeatedly stated his prophecy of 1939 was being fulfilled, namely, that a world war would bring about the annihilation of the Jewish race.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler approved the *Einsatzgruppen*—killing squads that followed the German army through Poland, the Baltic, and the Soviet Union—and was well informed about their activities.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] By summer 1942, Auschwitz concentration camp was expanded to accommodate large numbers of deportees for murder or enslavement.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Scores of other concentration camps and satellite camps were set up throughout Europe, with several camps devoted exclusively to extermination.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The victims were killed in concentration and extermination camps and in ghettos, and through mass shootings.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Many victims of the Holocaust were murdered in gas chambers or shot, while others died of starvation or disease or while working as slave labourers.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition to eliminating Jews, the Nazis planned to reduce the population of the conquered territories by 30 million people through starvation in an action called the Hunger Plan.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Food supplies would be diverted to the German army and German civilians.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Cities would be razed, and the land allowed to return to forest or resettled by German colonists.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Together, the Hunger Plan and *Generalplan Ost* would have led to the starvation of 80 million people in the Soviet Union.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] These partially fulfilled plans resulted in additional deaths, bringing the total number of civilians and prisoners of war who died in the democide to an estimated 19.3 million people.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies resulted in the killing of nearly two million non-Jewish Polish civilians, over three million Soviet prisoners of war, communists and other political opponents, homosexuals, the physically and mentally disabled, Jehovah's Witnesses, Adventists, and trade unionists.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler never spoke publicly about the killings and seems to have never visited the concentration camps.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The Nazis embraced the concept of racial hygiene.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 September 1935, Hitler presented two laws—known as the Nuremberg Laws—to the Reichstag.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws banned sexual relations and marriages between Aryans and Jews and were later extended to include "Gypsies, Negroes or their bastard offspring".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws stripped all non-Aryans of their German citizenship and forbade the employment of non-Jewish women under the age of 45 in Jewish households.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's early eugenic policies targeted children with physical and developmental disabilities in a programme dubbed Action Brandt, and he later authorised a euthanasia programme for adults with serious mental and physical disabilities, now referred to as *Aktion T4*.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ruled the Nazi Party autocratically by asserting the *Führerprinzip* (leader principle).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The principle relied on absolute obedience of all subordinates to their superiors; thus, he viewed the government structure as a pyramid, with himself—the infallible leader—at the apex.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Rank in the party was not determined by elections—positions were filled through appointment by those of higher rank, who demanded unquestioning obedience to the will of the leader.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership style was to give contradictory orders to his subordinates and to place them into positions where their duties and responsibilities overlapped with those of others, to have "the stronger one [do] the job".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In this way, Hitler fostered distrust, competition, and infighting among his subordinates to consolidate and maximise his own power.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] His cabinet never met after 1938, and he discouraged his ministers from meeting independently.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler typically did not give written orders; instead, he communicated verbally, or had them conveyed through his close associate Martin Bormann.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He entrusted Bormann with his paperwork, appointments, and personal finances; Bormann used his position to control the flow of information and access to Hitler.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler dominated his country's war effort during World War II to a greater extent than any other national leader.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He strengthened his control of the armed forces in 1938, and subsequently made all major decisions regarding Germany's military strategy.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] His decision to mount a risky series of offensives against Norway, France, and the Low Countries in 1940, against the advice of the military, proved successful, though the diplomatic and military strategies he employed in attempts to force the United Kingdom out of the war ended in failure.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler deepened his involvement in the war effort by appointing himself commander-in-chief of the Army in December 1941; from this point forward, he personally directed the war against the Soviet Union, while his military commanders facing the Western Allies retained a degree of autonomy.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership became increasingly disconnected from reality as the war turned against Germany, with the military's defensive strategies often hindered by his slow decision-making and frequent directives to hold untenable positions.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Nevertheless, he continued to believe that only his leadership could deliver victory.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In the final months of the war, Hitler refused to consider peace negotiations, regarding the destruction of Germany as preferable to surrender.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The military did not challenge Hitler's dominance of the war effort, and senior officers generally supported and enacted his decisions.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler created a public image as a celibate man without a domestic life, dedicated entirely to his political mission and the nation.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He met his lover, Eva Braun, in 1929, and married her on 29 April 1945, one day before they both committed suicide.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In September 1931, his half-niece, Geli Raubal, committed suicide with Hitler's gun in his Munich apartment.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] It was rumoured among contemporaries that Geli was in a romantic relationship with him, and her death was a source of deep, lasting pain.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Paula Hitler, the younger sister of Hitler and the last living member of his immediate family, died in June 1960.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was born to a practising Catholic mother and an anti-clerical father; after leaving home, Hitler never again attended Mass or received the sacraments.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Albert Speer stated that Hitler railed against the church to his political associates, and though he never officially left the church, he had no attachment to it.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer added that Hitler felt that in the absence of organised religion, people would turn to mysticism, which he considered regressive.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Speer, Hitler believed that Japanese religious beliefs or Islam would have been a more suitable religion for Germans than Christianity, with its "meekness and flabbiness".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Conway states that Hitler was fundamentally opposed to the Christian churches.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler did not believe in God, was anticlerical, and held Christian ethics in contempt because they contravened his preferred view of "survival of the fittest".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He favoured aspects of Protestantism that suited his own views, and adopted some elements of the Catholic Church's hierarchical organisation, liturgy, and phraseology.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In a 1932 speech, Hitler stated that he was not a Catholic, and declared himself a German Christian.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler viewed the church as an important politically conservative influence on society, and he adopted a strategic relationship with it that "suited his immediate political purposes".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In public, Hitler often praised Christian heritage and German Christian culture, though professing a belief in an "Aryan Jesus" who fought against the Jews.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] However, in *Hitler’s Table Talk* he was recorded as saying Christianity was an "absurdity" and nonsense founded on lies.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] According to a US Office of Strategic Services (OSS) report, "The Nazi Master Plan", Hitler planned to destroy the influence of Christian churches within the Reich.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Shirer commented that "the Nazi regime intended to destroy Christianity in Germany, if it could, and substitute the old paganism of the early tribal Germanic gods with the new paganism of the Nazi extremists".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler wanted to wait until after the war before executing this plan.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Richard Steigmann-Gall has concluded there was no firm evidence of such a plan to replace Christianity.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Swedish historian Mikael Nilsson notes that many of Hitler's religious statements are sourced from *Table Talk*, which he considers highly unreliable: much of the content was written days after the event and was heavily modified to suit the agendas of Martin Bormann and later François Genoud.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer wrote that Hitler had a negative view of Himmler's and Alfred Rosenberg's mystical notions and Himmler's attempt to mythologise the SS.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was more pragmatic, and his ambitions centred on more practical concerns.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Researchers have variously suggested that Hitler suffered from irritable bowel syndrome, skin lesions, irregular heartbeat, coronary sclerosis, Parkinson's disease, syphilis, giant-cell arteritis, tinnitus, and monorchism.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In a report prepared for the OSS in 1943, Walter Charles Langer of Harvard University described Hitler as a "neurotic psychopath" and speculated that he exhibited masochistic tendencies and deep feelings of self-loathing, which he projected onto others, particularly Jews.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In his 1977 book *The Psychopathic God: Adolf Hitler*, the historian Robert G.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Waite proposes that Hitler suffered from borderline personality disorder.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The historians Henrik Eberle and Hans-Joachim Neumann consider that while he suffered from several illnesses, including Parkinson's disease, Hitler did not experience pathological delusions and was always fully aware of, and therefore responsible for, his decisions.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Sometime in the 1930s, Hitler adopted a mainly vegetarian diet, avoiding all meat and fish from 1942 onwards.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] At social events, he sometimes gave graphic accounts of the slaughter of animals in an effort to make his guests shun meat.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Bormann had a greenhouse constructed near the Berghof (near Berchtesgaden) to ensure a steady supply of fresh fruit and vegetables for Hitler.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler stopped drinking alcohol around the time he became vegetarian and thereafter only very occasionally drank beer or wine on social occasions.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He was a non-smoker for most of his adult life, but smoked heavily in his youth (25 to 40 cigarettes a day); he eventually quit, calling the habit "a waste of money".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He encouraged his close associates to quit by offering a gold watch to anyone able to break the habit.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler began using amphetamine occasionally after 1937 and became addicted to it in late 1942.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer linked this use of amphetamine to Hitler's increasingly erratic behaviour and inflexible decision-making (for example, rarely allowing military retreats).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Prescribed 90 medications during the war years by his personal physician, Theodor Morell, Hitler took many pills each day for chronic stomach problems and other ailments.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He regularly consumed amphetamine, barbiturates, opiates, and cocaine, as well as potassium bromide and atropa belladonna (the latter in the form of Doktor Koster's Antigaspills).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He suffered ruptured eardrums as a result of the 20 July plot bomb blast in 1944, and 200 wood splinters had to be removed from his legs.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Newsreel footage of Hitler shows tremors in his left hand and a shuffling walk, which began before the war and worsened towards the end of his life.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Ernst-Günther Schenck and several other doctors who met Hitler in the last weeks of his life also formed a diagnosis of Parkinson's disease.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian Joachim Fest, Hitler's suicide was likened by numerous contemporaries to a "spell" being broken.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian John Toland, Nazism "burst like a bubble" without its leader.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw describes Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] "Never in history has such ruination—physical and moral—been associated with the name of one man", he adds.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's political programme brought about a world war, leaving behind a devastated and impoverished Eastern and Central Europe.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany suffered wholesale destruction, characterised as *Stunde Null* (Zero Hour).
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies inflicted human suffering on an unprecedented scale; according to R.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Rummel, the Nazi regime was responsible for the democidal killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre of World War II.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The number of civilians killed during the Second World War was unprecedented in the history of warfare.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians, philosophers, and politicians often use the word "evil" to describe the Nazi regime.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Many European countries have criminalised both the promotion of Nazism and Holocaust denial.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Friedrich Meinecke described Hitler as "one of the great examples of the singular and incalculable power of personality in historical life".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The English historian Hugh Trevor-Roper saw him as "among the 'terrible simplifiers' of history, the most systematic, the most historical, the most philosophical, and yet the coarsest, cruelest, least magnanimous conqueror the world has ever known".
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Roberts, Hitler's defeat marked the end of a phase of European history dominated by Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] In its place emerged the Cold War, a global confrontation between the Western Bloc, dominated by the United States and other NATO nations, and the Eastern Bloc, dominated by the Soviet Union.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Sebastian Haffner asserted that without Hitler and the displacement of the Jews, the modern nation-state of Israel would not exist.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He contends that without Hitler, the de-colonisation of former European spheres of influence would have been postponed.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Further, Haffner claimed that other than Alexander the Great, Hitler had a more significant impact than any other comparable historical figure, in that he too caused a wide range of worldwide changes in a relatively short time span.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler exploited documentary films and newsreels to inspire a cult of personality.
[src:alfred-schütz/adolf-hitler-p02] He was involved and appeared in a series of propaganda films throughout his political career, many made by Leni Riefenstahl, regarded as a pioneer of modern filmmaking.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The **University of Freiburg** (colloquially German: *Uni Freiburg*), officially the **Albert Ludwig University of Freiburg** (German: *Albert-Ludwigs-Universität Freiburg*), is a public research university located in Freiburg im Breisgau, Baden-Württemberg, Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university was founded in 1457 by the Habsburg dynasty as the second university in Austrian-Habsburg territory after the University of Vienna.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Today, Freiburg is the fifth-oldest university in Germany, with a long tradition of teaching the humanities, social sciences and natural sciences and technology and enjoys a high academic reputation both nationally and internationally.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university is made up of 11 faculties and attracts students from across Germany as well as from over 120 other countries.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Foreign students constitute about 18.2% of total student numbers.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg has been associated with figures such as Hannah Arendt, Rudolf Carnap, David Daube, Johann Eck, Hans-Georg Gadamer, Friedrich Hayek, Martin Heidegger, Edmund Husserl, Herbert Marcuse, Friedrich Meinecke, Edith Stein, Paul Uhlenhuth, Max Weber and Ernst Zermelo.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] As of October 2020, 22 Nobel laureates are affiliated with the University of Freiburg as alumni, faculty or researchers, and 15 academics have been honored with the highest German research prize, the Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize, while working at the university.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Originally Albrechts University, the university started with four faculties (theology, philosophy, medicine, and law).
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Its establishment belongs to the second wave of university foundings in the German-speaking world in the late Middle Ages, like the University of Tübingen and the University of Basel (Switzerland).
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Established by papal privilege (papal bull), the university in Freiburg actually was – like all or most universities in the Middle Ages – a corporation of the church body and therefore belonged to the Roman Catholic Church and its hierarchy.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The bishop of Basel consequently was its provost or chancellor (*Kanzler*), the bishop of Constance was its patron, and the real founder of the university was the sovereign, Archduke Albert VI of Austria, being the brother of Frederick III, Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire of the German Nation.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] At its founding, the university was named after Albert VI of Austria.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] He provided the university with land and endowments, as well as its own jurisdiction.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Also he declared Albrechts University as the "county university" (German *Landesuniversität*) for his territory until it was handed over to the Austrian House of Habsburg in 1490.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university soon attracted many students, such as the humanists Geiler von Kaysersberg, Johann Reuchlin, and Jakob Wimpfeling.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] When Ulrich Zasius was teaching law (until 1536), Freiburg became a centre of humanist jurisprudence.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] From 1529 to 1535, Erasmus of Rotterdam after having left Basel, lived and taught in Freiburg, however, never at the university.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] From around 1559 on, the university was housed at the *Altes Collegium* ("Old College"), today called the "new town-hall".
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The importance of the university decreased during the time of the Counter-Reformation.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] To counter reformatory tendencies, the administration of two faculties was handed over to the Roman Catholic order of the Jesuits in 1620.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] From 1682 on, the Jesuits built their college, as well as the Jesuit church (nowadays the "University Church" or *Universitätskirche*).
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In 1679, Freiburg temporarily became French territory, along with the southern parts of the upper Rhine.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] French King Louis XIV disliked the Austrian system and gave the Jesuits a free hand to operate the university.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] On 6 November 1684, a bilingual educational program was initiated.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] From 1686 to 1698, the faculty fled to Konstanz.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] After Freiburg was re-conquered and appointed as capital of Further Austria, a new time began for the university by the reforms of Empress Maria Theresa of Austria.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The requirements for admission were changed for all faculties in 1767 (before that time only Roman Catholics were allowed to study) and Natural Sciences were added as well as Public Administration.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Also in 1767, the university became a governmental institution despite the Church's protests.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The Church finally lost its predominant influence on the university when the Jesuits were suppressed following a decree signed by Pope Clement XIV in 1773.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Consequently, Johann Georg Jacobi (brother of the more famous philosopher Friedrich Heinrich Jacobi) in 1784 was the first Protestant professor teaching at the university in Freiburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] When Freiburg became a part of the newly established Grand Duchy of Baden in 1805 (after Napoleon occupied the area of the formerly Further Austria), a crisis began for the university in Freiburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university had enough endowments and earnings to survive until the beginning of the regency of Ludwig I, Grand Duke of Baden in 1818.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Finally in 1820, he saved the university with an annual contribution.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Since then, the university has been named Albert Ludwigs University of Freiburg (*Albert-Ludwigs-Universität Freiburg*) as an acknowledgement of gratitude by the university and the citizens of Freiburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In the 1880s, the population of the student body and faculty started to grow quickly.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The scientific reputation of Albert Ludwigs University attracted several researchers such as economist Adolph Wagner, historians Georg von Below and Friedrich Meinecke, and jurists Karl von Amira and Paul Lenel.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In 1900, Freiburg became the first German university to accept female students.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Before there had been no women at German universities.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In the beginning of the 20th century, several new university buildings were built in the centre of Freiburg, such as the new main building in 1911.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university counted 3,000 students just before World War I.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] After World War I, the philosophers Edmund Husserl and Martin Heidegger (since 1928) taught at Albert Ludwigs University, as well as Edith Stein.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In the field of social sciences, Walter Eucken developed the idea of ordoliberalism, which subsequently is known as the "Freiburg School".
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] During the time of the Nazi dictatorship, the university went through the process of "political alignment" (*Gleichschaltung*) like the rest of the German universities.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Under the rector Martin Heidegger, all Jewish faculty members were forced to leave the university in accordance with the Law for the Restoration of the Professional Civil Service.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] He also informed the Gestapo of the pacifist leanings of a distinguished Faculty member, Hermann Staudinger.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The Nazi geneticist Eugen Fischer promoted racist views while a member of the university, ideas which were used to support the notorious Nuremberg laws passed by the Nazis.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] After World War II, the University of Freiburg was reopened.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] New buildings for natural sciences were erected in the *Institutsviertel* ("institute quarter").
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In the postwar years, the ideas of ordoliberalism, developed earlier by economists of the Freiburg School, such as Walter Eucken, Franz Böhm, Hans Grossmann-Doerth, and Leonhard Miksch, drove the creation of the German social market economy and its attendant *Wirtschaftswunder*.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Nobel Prize winner and former professor at the University of Freiburg, Friedrich Hayek, is also associated with this theory.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] He directed the Walter Eucken Institut, an economic think tank in Freiburg cooperating with the university.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Arnold Bergstraesser, considered a founding father or German political science after World War II, was also a professor at the University of Freiburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] His research group later formed what is now the Arnold Bergstraesser Institute for sociocultural research at the university.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In the late 20th century, the university was part of a mass education campaign and expanded rapidly.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The student body grew to 10,000 by the 1960s, and doubled to 20,000 students by 1980.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In the 1970s, the faculty structure was changed to 14 departments, with the Faculty of Engineering becoming the 15th faculty in 1994.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In 2002, the number of faculties was reduced to 11.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university opened a memorial dedicated to the victims of National Socialism among the students, staff, and faculty in 2003.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In 2006, the University of Freiburg joined the League of European Research Universities (LERU).
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] One year later, the university was chosen as one of nine German Universities of Excellence.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] However, it did not receive the third line of funding in 2012.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The seal of the University of Freiburg depicts Christ seated on a gothic throne holding the gospel in his right hand with the temple curtain in the background.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Christ offers the teachings of the gospel to the Jewish scholars who are crouched at his feet.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] To the left and right of Christ are structures resembling towers, most likely symbolic of the Temple of Jerusalem.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Located to the right of Christ is the coat of arms of the Austrian duchies, a banner with five eagles.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The shield on the opposite side symbolizes the coat of arms used by the Habsburgs in conjunction with their territories.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The coat of arms of the city of Freiburg is located at the bottom of the seal, displaying St George's Cross.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The Latin inscription on the seal reads *Sigillum universitatis studii friburgensis brisgaudie*.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The seal was slightly modified in 1913, but has otherwise been in continuous use since it was adopted in 1462.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Having grown with the city since the 15th century, the university's buildings are deeply intertwined with the city.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The three large campuses are the university center next to the historical city center, the institutes quarter, and the engineering campus, but other buildings can be found scattered throughout Freiburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university complex in the historical center of Freiburg contains such picturesque buildings as the Jugendstil *Kollegiengebäude I*(short: "KG I"), built in 1911 by Hermann Billing, and the gothic revival old university library.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The current University Library is also located in the historical center; it is a monumental building erected in the 1970s, and was to be renovated and redesigned beginning in September 2008.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] It is one of the largest in Germany and placed fourth in an October 2007, German national ranking of university libraries.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University Church, located across from *Kollegiengebäude II* (short: "KG II"), was built in 1683 by the Jesuit order.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The church and the Jesuit college were handed over to the university after the Jesuit order was suppressed in 1773.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The church was destroyed in the 27 November 1944, bombing raid on Freiburg, and reconstructed in 1956.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The "institute quarter" (*Institutsviertel*) is home to the science faculties.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] This campus was destroyed almost completely in the Freiburg bombing raid in 1944.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] After World War II, the reconstruction of the institutes began.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Today, the quarter houses the physics buildings, the tall main chemistry building, visible from afar, the famous Institute for Macromolecular Chemistry at the Hermann-Staudinger-Haus, various other science buildings, and the preclinical institutes of the Faculty of Medicine.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The engineering campus is located next to the small Freiburg airfield to the northwest of the city center, close to the University Medical Center.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The campus is home to the *Institut für Mikrosystemtechnik* ( Department of Microsystems Engineering) and the Department of Computer Science.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] With the addition of the Faculty of Engineering, the University of Freiburg became the first classical university to combine traditional disciplines with microsystems technologies.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University Medical Center (*Universitätsklinikum Freiburg*) is one of Germany's largest medical centers.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] It boasts 1,600 beds and handles 55,000 in-patients a year, with another 357,000 being treated as out-patients.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] It consists of 13 specialized clinics, five clinical institutes, and five centers (e.g.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University Medical Center achieved many technical advances, such as the first implantation of an artificial heart *Jarvik 2000* in 2002.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Most recently, the University of Freiburg purchased a large historic villa in the district of Herdern, which will house part of the literature and linguistics, as well as history departments of the Freiburg Institute for Advanced Studies.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In 2015, the University of Freiburg opened its new library, housed in a modern building with a large glass and chrome facade.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The library features a section for quiet work and the permanent collection as well as space for group work, where collaboration is encouraged.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The building also includes a student cafe and an outdoor plaza with modern sculpture.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university has a combined undergraduate and graduate student population of around 21,600.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] About 16% of these students are foreigners, from about 120 countries.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Admission largely depends on the faculty and program applied for and is strictly merit based, with the average score of final secondary-school examinations (German *Abitur*) or A-levels playing an important role.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Overall, in the fall of 2010, roughly 4,000 of around 26,000 applicants were admitted: this means that the university's acceptance rate that year was equal to 15.38%.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg offers a large variety of undergraduate, graduate, and postdoctoral degree programs at its 11 faculties in 150 fields of study.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] As common among German universities, the academic year consists of summer and winter terms (semesters).
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The winter term runs from 1 October to 31 March, while the summer term runs from 1 April to 30 September.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] However, lectures and classes usually do not run for the full duration of these periods and allow for breaks in spring and fall.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] As a German university, tuition is mostly free.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg currently has a semester fee of 180 EUR for all undergraduate and most graduate and doctoral programs.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Additionally, since autumn 2017, non-EU students are charged 1500 EUR tuition fee per semester.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Numerous student clubs and organizations are active, among them a campus news station, uniCROSS which is a cross-media platform run by students.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] It consists of the "uniFM" team, which brings the news as a radio format, the "uniTV" team, producing videos and the "uniONLINE" team which is responsible for the magazine.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Because of the nearby French and Swiss borders and the adjacent Black Forest, where the university owns a retreat on Schauinsland Mountain, fine opportunities exist for leisure and outdoor activities.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Students come from Central and Eastern Europe for language studies, the majority demographic category is females in age range 18–25 (58%).
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university provides student housing in its various dormitories, run by the *Studentenwerk*.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Additionally, further dormitories in Freiburg are operated by other institutions, such as the Catholic Archdiocese.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Due to the affordable rent and limited spots, rooms in the various dormitories are very popular.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Many students find private living arrangements, such as *Wohngemeinschaften* (shared apartments).
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] However, the popularity of Freiburg for prospective students can make finding an apartment or room quite time-consuming, especially before the start of the academic terms.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university has its own career center, singled out as one of the best in Germany by the *Stifterverband für die Deutsche Wissenschaft*.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university scored well with its submissions to the German Universities Excellence Initiative.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university received funding in all three categories.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] To that end, the university founded the Freiburg Institute for Advanced Studies (FRIAS).
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Being selected for the third category ranks Freiburg as one of nine "excellence universities" in Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university is to receive over EUR 130 million in additional funds over five years (from 2007) from this third category of funding.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In 2009, the university was also successful in a nationwide competition for excellence in teaching, held by the *Stifterverband der deutschen Wissenschaft*.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg, with its plans for future innovative teaching concepts, was selected as one of 10 winners from a field of over 100 higher education institutions.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Citing insufficient evidence of integration of the FRIAS concept into the university's framework, the committee did not extend funding for the FRIAS and the institutional strategy line of funding, despite acknowledging the impressive research and advances achieved at FRIAS in the past years.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg is recognized in several university ranking systems.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In the *QS World University Rankings* 2024, it holds the 192nd position globally and the 9th position nationally.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* 2024 placed it 128th in the world and 11th in Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The *Academic Ranking of World Universities* (*ARWU*) 2023 ranks it between 101st and 150th globally, and 5th nationally.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In university rankings published in 2007 and 2008 by German magazines and periodicals (*Der Spiegel, Die Zeit, Focus*, etc.) the University of Freiburg has established itself as one of Germany's top universities.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The faculties for law, medicine, economics, history, English studies, German studies, biology, dentistry, and pharmacology achieve especially high scores.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In regards to the natural sciences, the University of Freiburg ranked sixth in Europe and second in Germany in a ranking from 2003 of the European Commission of the universities according to their overall impact on scientific research.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The Centre for Higher Education Development, a German higher education think tank, periodically publishes comprehensive rankings of European Master's and PhD programs.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In 2016, Freiburg garnered five spots in the top Excellence Group among seven subject fields examined.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In a recent survey by the Nature Publishing Group, the *Nature Publishing Index – 2012 Global Top 100*, the University of Freiburg was the highest-ranked German university and ranked 66th worldwide and 18th in Europe.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] A recent study, "Benchmarking China and Germany: An Analysis of Patent Portfolios of Universities and Research Organizations", was published in May 2013 and sought to evaluate leading universities and research institutions in Germany and China in regards to their patent applications.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The study placed the University of Freiburg as the third-most innovative university in Germany in terms of total patent applications.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Teams of the University of Freiburg frequently participate in academic competitions with considerable success.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The moot court team of the Faculty of Law has been the most successful team in the history of the competition Willem C.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Vis International Commercial Arbitration Moot.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The humanoid robot team of the Faculty of Engineering regularly competes with distinction in international tournaments.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg team has also repeatedly scored highly at the International Genetically Engineered Machine undergraduate synthetic biology competition held at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The team was supported by numerous university institutions, among them the recently established *bioss* cluster of excellence.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg also participates in the National Model United Nations held annually in New York City.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The genetically engineered golden rice was developed by the University of Freiburg (Peter Beyer) and the ETH Zurich (Ingo Potrykus) from 1992 to 2000.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] It was considered a breakthrough in biotechnology at the time of publication and now can help to provide vitamin A to people lacking access to it in their diets.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] When previous rector Jäger retired in 2008, law professor Andreas Voßkuhle was chosen as his successor.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] However, shortly after the start of his term, the Social Democratic Party of Germany nominated Voßkuhle as vice-president of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Voßkuhle accepted the nomination, was confirmed, and took his seat on the court in May 2008.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In July 2008, then vice-rector Hans-Jochen Schiewer was elected as successor to Voßkuhle.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Schiewer has assumed the position of rector with the start of the winter term 2008/2009.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg offers educational audio and video contents on the iTunes U software platform since January 2008.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg Institute of Physics is actively involved with research at the Large Hadron Collider and has contributed significantly to the ATLAS experiment, resulting in the discovery of the Higgs boson in 2012.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Today, about 430 professors, 3,695 academic employees, and 8,644 non-academic employees at the university are working for the Albert Ludwigs University, making it Freiburg's and the region's biggest employer.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university attracts many academics from abroad and was awarded excellent positions in the 2005 and 2009 *Humboldt Ranking*.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] University College Freiburg (UCF) is the university's central facility for promoting and administering international, interdisciplinary teaching activities.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] It was established in 2012 and is situated in the historical buildings of the old university, the historical site of the *artes liberales*.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] UCF serves as a lab for innovative teaching approaches and instructional design at the University of Freiburg and works in close co-operation with the faculties and the Rectorate's departments for Instructional Development and International Relations.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] It is accredited by the University of Freiburg, which draws its authority from the Central Evaluation and Accreditation Agency.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The four-year, English-taught Bachelor program in Liberal Arts and Sciences (LAS) is UCF's major offering, the first of its kind in Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] It emphasizes a broad interdisciplinary education, while at the same time providing for individualized academic concentrations on a high academic level.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Students have to complete 240 ECTS credits and are able to major in life sciences, environmental and sustainability sciences, culture and history and governance.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Electives can be taken at UCF, in the greater University of Freiburg, during studies abroad or in the form of internships and self-directed practical projects.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In order to provide a framework and didactic guidance for interdisciplinary higher education, the University of Freiburg has established two chairs at UCF: Epistemology and Theory of Science (Prof.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Frieder Vogelmann, who is also the dean of studies) and Science and Technology Studies (Prof.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The college and the program are directed by Managing Director Paul Sterzel and the Academic Coordinator Thorsten Leiendecker.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Students at UCF organize a number of interest groups, for instance a magazine publishing group, a 3D printing group, an arts collective, and a Model United Nations team.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] They represented by an elected board of twelve student office holders.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Alumni are a part of a subgroup within the greater University of Freiburg alumni association.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg has a variety of graduate education and research opportunities.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In an evaluation of European graduate programs, Freiburg was ranked among the leading universities in several subject fields examined.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] One of the notable graduate opportunities is the Freiburg Institute for Advanced Studies, a project funded by the German Excellence Initiative.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Apart from the many graduate programs of its faculties, Freiburg has set up additional specialized graduate schools and graduate research centers, coordinated by the newly founded International Graduate Academy (IGA) Freiburg.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg has offered German language courses for foreign students since 1911.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The courses take place at the university's Language Teaching Centre ('Sprachlehrinstitut') during the semester breaks and attract students from over 50 nations..
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The intensive language lessons are bolstered by a supplementary program with lectures and seminars on German culture, politics, philosophy, and art, as well as excursions to the Black Forest, the Alsace region in France, Basel (Switzerland) or Lake Constance.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In addition to classes for all language levels, professional German courses (e.g. business German) are also offered.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The city of Freiburg is known for its environmentally friendly policies and focus on renewable energy and sustainability, attracting solar industry and research to the city.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] This environmentally conscious attitude also extends to the University of Freiburg which has founded the work group "Nachhaltige Universität Freiburg" (Sustainable University of Freiburg) and has drawn up environmental guidelines to be implemented in university practice.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university has also founded the initiative Solar-Uni Freiburg in 2007, with the aim of further expanding its capabilities in sustainability and environmental research.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Solar panels were installed on the roofs of university buildings.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] To bundle renewable energy research and teaching at the university, the Center for Renewable Energy (ZEE, Zentrum für Erneuerbare Energien), an interdisciplinary and cross-faculty facility, was founded.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Aside from research in the fields of solar energy, biomass, geothermal energy, energy efficiency and new energies, an international Master of Science degree in Renewable Energy Management is being offered.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg cooperates closely with external research institutions located in Freiburg, several of which are connected with chairs at the university.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university is part of the regional EUCOR federation together with the Karlsruhe Institute of Technology, the universities of Basel, Mulhouse, and, marked by particularly close ties, Strasbourg.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Freiburg is further a member of the League of European Research Universities; the European University Association; ASEA-Uninet; AC21; and the International Forum of Public Universities (IFPU).
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university also has exchange agreements and cooperative efforts with universities on almost every continent.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The University of Freiburg initiated an English language international master's program in social sciences, the Global Studies Programme (GSP) in 2001.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The aim of the program is to enable students to study social sciences in different regions and cultures.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Combining various disciplines such as sociology, political sciences, anthropology and geography, students approach globalization with a unique perspective.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Students in the GSP master's program study on three different continents during the two-year degree program.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Since 2008, the GSP also offers a PhD program in Global Studies.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The Global Studies Program has received many awards, among them the BMW Group Award for Intercultural Learning in 2004 as well as being listed a Top Ten International master's degree Course in Germany by the German Academic Exchange Service (DAAD) in 2006.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] In 1995, the University of Freiburg helped the Aromanian professor Vasile Barba found the European Center of Aromanian Studies (Aromanian: *Tsentrul European ti Studii Armãneshti*; German: *Europäisches Zentrum für Aromunische Studien*), specialized on Aromanian studies.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] The university also supports the Institute for Russian-German Literature and Cultural Relations at the Russian State University for the Humanities as well as the Vladimir Admoni School for Doctoral Studies at the University of Latvia.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Approximately 1/6th of its students are international students.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Many students at this university participate in the ERASMUS exchange program.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Perhaps best known amongst the alumni of the university are Joseph Goebbels, Martin Heidegger, Edmund Husserl, Hannah Arendt, Paul Ehrlich, Hans Krebs, Hans Spemann, Ethel Dench Puffer Howes, and Friedrich Hayek.
[src:alfred-schütz/albert-ludwigs-universität] Among the affiliates are numerous Nobel laureates and Leibniz Prize winners.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz was born on 13 April 1899 in Vienna, Austria, as the only child in an upper-middle-class Jewish family.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Following his graduation from high school, he was drafted into the Austrian Army where he quickly rose to the American equivalent rank of second lieutenant.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] His army regiment was dispatched to fight in a series of heavy battles on the Italian front (WWI).
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] In 1918, Schutz enrolled at the University of Vienna, where he earned his law degree.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] He also enrolled at the Viennese Academy of International Trade from 1919 to 1920, specialising in international law.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] During his time at the University of Vienna, attending lectures given by Max Weber, Schutz came to the conclusion that Weber had left the problem of *meaning* unexplicated.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] As noted by Helmut Wagner (1983), Schutz's fascination with this problem was a result of his experience in combat, combined with returning to starving and economically decimated Vienna.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Partly because there were few academic posts available, he developed a well-established and prominent career in international banking, He became the chief financial officer for Reitler and Company, the Vienna banking firm.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] His academic work was done in his spare time.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] He was once described by Edmund Husserl as "a banker by day and a philosopher by night." In 1933, the threat of Adolf Hitler's rise in Germany caused Schutz and other Viennese intellectuals to flee Austria and seek asylum in allied countries.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz and his family relocated to Paris in 1938 in political exile.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] He continued to work for Reitler and Company as an international lawyer.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] He moved to the United States in 1939, where he became a part-time faculty member of The New School.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] There, he taught sociology and philosophy, as well as serving as chair of the Philosophy department.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz received a substantial amount of assistance from his wife, Ilse, who transcribed his working notes and letters from his taped dictations.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz died on 20 May 1959 in New York City at the age of 60.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Four volumes of Collected Papers were published posthumously, along with the draft of a second book he had been working on prior to his death.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz was strongly influenced by Ludwig von Mises, Henri Bergson, William James, and Edmund Husserl, as well as Max Weber.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Drawing on phenomenology, Schutz's principal aim was to create a philosophical foundation for the social sciences.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] While Schutz's work paralleled George Herbert Mead’s analysis of the meanings within social interactions, Schutz was highly critical of Mead’s behavioristic approach.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Although Schutz was never a student of Husserl, he and colleague Felix Kaufmann intensively studied Husserl's work in order to seek a basis for Weber's interpretive sociology and for Austrian economic theory.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] In 1932, Schutz’s efforts resulted in his first published book, *Der sinnhafte Aufbau der sozialen Welt* ('The Meaningful Structure of the Social World') which was published in English as *The Phenomenology of the Social World*.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz argues that social science must be grounded in analysis of what Husserl referred to as 'the natural attitude', the assumptions that structure everyday perceptions and actions in the social world.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz retains Weber's conception of social science as properly committed to the principle of value neutrality, but also to value relevance, and that its investigations must rely on “ideal types”.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] He viewed the technique of bracketing, drawn from Husserlian phenomenology, as a way beyond the limitations of ideal-type analysis.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] This publication brought him to the attention of Husserl, whom he visited frequently and corresponded with until Husserl's death in 1938.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Even so, when Husserl asked Schutz to be his assistant, he was unable to accept the offer at Freiburg University for personal reasons.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz's main area of concern was the ways in which people grasp the consciousness of others while living within their own streams of consciousness.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] He spoke much about intersubjectivity, in a broader sense, using it in reference to the social world, specifically the social nature of knowledge.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] A great deal of his work deals with the "lifeworld," in which people create social reality under the constraints of preexisting social and cultural factors and structures.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz is also known for his belief that humans attempt to typify everything; i.e., to categorize people and things to better understand them within the context of society.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] He believed that the various typifications we use inform how we understand and interact with people and objects in the social world.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz's theories and conceptions are illuminated through an intense and insightful correspondence with Harvard scholar Talcott Parsons.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] The thrust of the discussion centered on the meaning of the concept "social action." Whether the Schutz-Parsons correspondence can be characterized as “dialogue” rather than “debate” has been analyzed by Rehorick (1980).
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Further insights into the fundamental differences between Schutz and Parsons is provided by a critical examination of original correspondence that brought in a third scholarly voice—that of Eric Voegelin.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] This discussion shows that conceptual and theoretical differences between Schutz and Parsons stem from different “ways of knowing,” implying fundamentally different orientations toward social scientific thought.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz's writings have had a lasting impact on the social sciences, both on phenomenological approaches to sociology and in ethnomethodology (through the writings of Harold Garfinkel).
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Heavily influenced by Schutz's work as his student, Thomas Luckmann ultimately finished Schutz's work on the structures of the lifeworld by filling out his unfinished notes after Schutz died.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Berger and Luckmann went on to use Schutz's work to further understand human culture and reality, through the development of a new form of the sociology of knowledge.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Phenomenology is the study of things as they appear (i.e., *phenomena*).
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Phenomenology originated with Edmund Husserl, who Schutz studied and even met.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] There are many assumptions behind phenomenology that help explain its creation.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] First, it rejects the concept of objective research: phenomenologists would rather group presumptions through a process called *phenomenological epoche*.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Second, phenomenology believes that analyzing the daily human behavior will provide one with a comprehensive understanding of nature.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] The third assumption is that persons, not individuals, should be explored and questioned.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Sociologically speaking, this is in part because persons can be better understood by the unique ways they reflect and symbolize the society they live in.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Fourth, phenomenologists prefer to gather *capta*, or *conscious experience*, rather than traditional data.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Finally, phenomenology is considered to be oriented on discovery, and therefore phenomenologists gather research using methods that are far less restricting than in other sciences.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Social phenomenology is concerned with how people use ordinary, everyday interactions to produce a feeling of reality and intersubjectivity.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Most of Schutz's work concerned the methods used for the construction of reality through everyday experiences.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] The social construction of reality and ethnomethodology are disciplinary extensions beyond the social phenomenology of Alfred Schutz.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] As noted by Farganis (2011), phenomenological sociology is characterized as particularly subjective in nature because its emphasis of understanding reality through the perspective of the acting subject rather than through the lens of the scientific observer.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] There is this existence of meaning that comes into play, yet most people simply accept the world how it is and never second guess the concept or problem of meaning.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz delves even more into specific relationships such as the difference between intimate face-to-face relationships and distant and impersonal relationships.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz's division of Husserl's *lebenswelt* (the mundane 'lifeworld') into four distinct sub-worlds is perhaps his most influential theoretical contribution.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] 2. social reality that is on the horizon of direct experience.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] The former consists of the *umwelt* ('environment'), the environment defined through the perception and action of agents.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] 3. the world of successors (*folgewelt*).
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] The last two represent the past and the future, whereas one's contemporaries share a community of time, if not space, and are different from the predecessors and successors because it is possible for them to become fellow-men or consociates.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] Schutz was interested in documenting the transition from direct to indirect experience and the series of experiences in between.
[src:alfred-schütz/alfred-schütz] In his later writings, Schutz explored how everyday social experiences that pertain to these dimensions are most often intertwined in varying degrees of anonymity.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] The ***American Journal of Sociology*** (abbreviated ***AJS***) is a bimonthly peer-reviewed academic journal that publishes original research and book reviews in the field of sociology and related social sciences.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] It was founded in 1895 as the first journal in its discipline.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] Along with the *American Sociological Review*, it is considered one of the top journals in the academic field of sociology.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] For its entire history, the journal has been housed at the University of Chicago and published by the University of Chicago Press.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] For its first thirty years, the American Sociological Society (now the American Sociological Association) was largely dominated by the Department of Sociology at the University of Chicago, and the quasi-official journal of the association was the *American Journal of Sociology*.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] The first issue of the *American Journal of Sociology* was published in July 1895.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] In the first 25 years of the journal, the most prominent subjects were social theory and social psychology.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] In the 1920s, statistical work became increasingly prominent in the journal.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] Over the period 1920–1944, the journal's most prominent subject matters were social theory, social psychology, human ecology, and institutional theory.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] From 1926 to 1933, the journal was co-edited by a number of different members of the University of Chicago faculty including Ellsworth Faris, Robert E.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] Park, Ernest Burgess, Fay-Cooper Cole, Marion Talbot, Frederick Starr, Edward Sapir, Louis Wirth, Eyler Simpson, Edward Webster, Edwin Sutherland, William Ogburn, Herbert Blumer, and Robert Redfield.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, its 2019 impact factor was 3.232, ranking it 8th out of 150 journals in the category "Sociology".
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] In 2002, the *American Journal of Sociology* created the Roger V.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] Gould prize in memory of its former editor.
[src:alfred-schütz/american-journal-of-sociology] Mare, Shelley Correll, and Roberto Garvía.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] There are various situations in which a person might choose to remain anonymous.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Acts of charity have been performed anonymously when benefactors do not wish to be acknowledged.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] A person who feels threatened might attempt to mitigate that threat through anonymity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] A witness to a crime might seek to avoid retribution, for example, by anonymously calling a crime tipline.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In many other situations (like conversation between strangers, or buying some product or service in a shop), anonymity is traditionally accepted as natural.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Some writers have argued that the term "namelessness", though technically correct, does not capture what is more centrally at stake in contexts of anonymity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The important idea here is that a person be non-identifiable, unreachable, or untrackable.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity is also seen as a way to realize certain other values, such as privacy or liberty.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] An important example of anonymity being not only protected, but enforced, by law is in voting in free elections.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Criminals might proceed anonymously to conceal their participation in a crime.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In certain situations, however, it may be illegal to remain anonymous.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] For example, 24 of the U.S. states have "stop and identify" statutes that require persons detained to self-identify when requested by a law enforcement officer, when the person is reasonably suspected of committing a crime.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Over the past few years, anonymity tools used on the dark web by criminals and malicious users have drastically altered the ability of law enforcement to use conventional surveillance techniques.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The term "anonymous message" typically refers to a message that does not reveal its sender.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In many countries, anonymous letters are protected by law and must be delivered as regular letters.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In mathematics, in reference to an arbitrary element (e.g., a human, an object, a computer), within a well-defined set (called the "anonymity set"), "anonymity" of that element refers to the property of that element of not being identifiable within this set.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] If it is not identifiable, then the element is said to be "anonymous".
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The word anonymous was borrowed into English around 1600 from the Late Latin word "anonymus", from Ancient Greek ᾰ̓νώνῠμος (anṓnumos, "without name"), from ᾰ̓ν- (an-, "un-") with ὄνῠμᾰ (ónuma), Aeolic and Doric dialectal form of ὄνομᾰ (ónoma, "name").
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Sometimes a person may desire a long-term relationship (such as a reputation) with another party without necessarily disclosing personally identifying information to that party.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In this case, it may be useful for the person to establish a unique identifier, called a pseudonym.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Examples of pseudonyms are pen names, nicknames, credit card numbers, student numbers, bank account numbers, etc.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] A pseudonym enables the other party to link different messages from the same person and, thereby, to establish a long-term relationship.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Pseudonyms are widely used in social networks and other virtual communication, although recently some important service providers like Google try to discourage pseudonymity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Someone using a pseudonym would be strictly considered to be using "pseudonymity" not "anonymity", but sometimes the latter is used to refer to both (in general, a situation where the legal identity of the person is disguised).
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity may reduce the accountability one perceives to have for their actions, and removes the impact these actions might otherwise have on their reputation.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This can have dramatic effects, both useful and harmful to various parties involved.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Thus, it may be used for psychological tactics involving any respective party to purport or support or discredit any sort of activity or belief.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In conversational settings, anonymity may allow people to reveal personal history and feelings without fear of later embarrassment.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Electronic conversational media can provide physical isolation, in addition to anonymity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This prevents physical retaliation for remarks, and prevents negative or taboo behavior or discussion from tarnishing the reputation of the speaker.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This can be beneficial when discussing very private matters, or taboo subjects or expressing views or revealing facts that may put someone in physical, financial, or legal danger (such as illegal activity, or unpopular, or outlawed political views).
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In work settings, the three most common forms of anonymous communication are traditional suggestion boxes, written feedback, and Caller ID blocking.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Additionally, the appropriateness of anonymous organizational communication varies depending on the use, with organizational surveys or assessments typically perceived as highly appropriate and firing perceived as highly inappropriate.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity use and appropriateness have also been found to be significantly related to the quality of relationships with key others at work.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] With few perceived negative consequences, anonymous or semi-anonymous forums often provide a soapbox for disruptive conversational behavior.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The term "troll" is sometimes used to refer to those who engage in such disruptive behavior.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Relative anonymity is often enjoyed in large crowds.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Different people have different psychological and philosophical reactions to this development, especially as a modern phenomenon.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This anonymity is an important factor in crowd psychology, and behavior in situations such as a riot.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This perceived anonymity can be compromised by technologies such as photography.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Groupthink behavior and conformity are also considered to be an established effect of internet anonymity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity also permits highly trained professionals such as judges to freely express themselves regarding the strategies they employ to perform their jobs objectively.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymous commercial transactions can protect the privacy of consumers.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Some consumers prefer to use cash when buying everyday goods (like groceries or tools), to prevent sellers from aggregating information or soliciting them in the future.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Credit cards are linked to a person's name, and can be used to discover other information, such as postal address, phone number, etc.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The ecash system was developed to allow secure anonymous transactions.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Another example would be Enymity, which actually makes a purchase on a customer's behalf.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] When purchasing taboo goods and services, anonymity makes many potential consumers more comfortable with or more willing to engage in the transaction.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Many loyalty programs use cards that personally identify the consumer engaging in each transaction (possibly for later solicitation, or for redemption or security purposes), or that act as a numerical pseudonym, for use in data mining.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity can also be used as a protection against legal prosecution.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] For example, when committing unlawful actions, many criminals attempt to avoid identification by the means of obscuring/covering their faces with scarves or masks, and wear gloves or other hand coverings in order to not leave any fingerprints.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In organized crime, groups of criminals may collaborate on a certain project without revealing to each other their names or other personally identifiable information.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The movie *The Thomas Crown Affair* depicted a fictional collaboration by people who had never previously met and did not know who had recruited them.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The anonymous purchase of a gun or knife to be used in a crime helps prevent linking an abandoned weapon to the identity of the perpetrator.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] There are two aspects, one, giving to a large charitable organization obscures the beneficiary of a donation from the benefactor, the other is giving anonymously to obscure the benefactor both from the beneficiary and from everyone else.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymous charity has long been a widespread and durable moral precept of many ethical and religious systems, as well as being in practice a widespread human activity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] A benefactor may not wish to establish any relationship with the beneficiary, particularly if the beneficiary is perceived as being unsavory.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Benefactors may not wish to identify themselves as capable of giving.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] A benefactor may wish to improve the world, as long as no one knows who did it, out of modesty, wishing to avoid publicity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Another reason for anonymous charity is a benefactor who does not want a charitable organization to pursue them for more donations, sometimes aggressively.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Attempts at anonymity are not always met with support from society.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity sometimes clashes with the policies and procedures of governments or private organizations.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In the United States, disclosure of identity is required to be able to vote, though the secret ballot prevents disclosure of individual voting patterns.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In airports in most countries, passengers are not allowed to board flights unless they have identified themselves to airline or transportation security personnel, typically in the form of the presentation of an identification card.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] On the other hand, some policies and procedures require anonymity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Stylometric identification of anonymous authors by writing style is a potential risk, which is expected to grow as analytic techniques improve and computing power and text corpora grow.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Authors may resist such identification by practicing adversarial stylometry.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] When it is necessary to refer to someone who is anonymous, it is typically necessary to create a type of pseudo-identification for that person.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In literature, the most common way to state that the identity of an author is unknown is to refer to them as simply "Anonymous".
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This is usually the case with older texts in which the author is long dead and unable to claim authorship of a work.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] When the work claims to be that of some famous author the pseudonymous author is identified as "Pseudo-", as in Pseudo-Dionysius the Areopagite, an author claiming—and long believed—to be Dionysius the Areopagite, an early Christian convert.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In the history of art, many painting workshops can be identified by their characteristic style and discussed and the workshop's output set in chronological order.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Sometimes archival research later identifies the name, as when the "Master of Flémalle"—defined by three paintings in the Städelsches Kunstinstitut in Frankfurt— was identified as Robert Campin.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The 20th-century art historian Bernard Berenson methodically identified numerous early Renaissance Florentine and Sienese workshops under such sobriquets as "Amico di Sandro" for an anonymous painter in the immediate circle of Sandro Botticelli.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In legal cases, a popularly accepted name to use when it is determined that an individual needs to maintain anonymity is "John Doe".
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This name is often modified to "Jane Doe" when the anonymity-seeker is female.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The same names are also commonly used when the identification of a dead person is not known.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The semi-acronym Unsub is used as law enforcement slang for "Unknown Subject of an Investigation".
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The military often feels a need to honor the remains of soldiers for whom identification is impossible.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In many countries, such a memorial is named the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Most modern newspapers and magazines attribute their articles to individual editors, or to news agencies.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] An exception is the British weekly *The Economist.* All British newspapers run their leaders, or editorials, anonymously.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] *The Economist* fully adopts this policy, saying "Many hands write *The Economist*, but it speaks with a collective voice".
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Guardian considers that *"people will often speak more honestly if they are allowed to speak anonymously"*.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] According to Ross Eaman, in his book *The A to Z of Journalism*, until the mid-19th century, most writers in Great Britain, especially the less well known, did not sign their names to their work in newspapers, magazines and reviews.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Most commentary on the Internet is essentially done anonymously, using unidentifiable pseudonyms.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] However, this has been widely discredited in a study by the University of Birmingham, which found that the number of people who use the internet anonymously is statistically the same as the number of people who use the internet to interact with friends or known contacts.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] While these usernames can take on an identity of their own, they are sometimes separated and anonymous from the actual author.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] According to the University of Stockholm this is creating more freedom of expression, and less accountability.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Wikipedia is collaboratively written mostly by authors using either unidentifiable pseudonyms or temporary account identifiers, although many Wikipedia editors use their real names instead of pseudonyms.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This address can be mapped to a particular Internet service provider (ISP), and this ISP can then provide information about what customer that IP address was leased to.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This does not necessarily implicate a specific individual (because other people could be using that customer's connection, especially if the customer is a public resource, such as a library), but it provides regional information and serves as powerful circumstantial evidence.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymizing services such as I2P and Tor address the issue of IP tracking.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In short, they work by encrypting packets within multiple layers of encryption.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The packet follows a predetermined route through the anonymizing network.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Each router sees the immediate previous router as the origin and the immediate next router as the destination.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Thus, no router ever knows both the true origin and destination of the packet.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This makes these services more secure than centralized anonymizing services (where a central point of knowledge exists).
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Sites such as Chatroulette, Omegle, and Tinder (which pair up random users for a conversation) capitalized on a fascination with anonymity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Apps like Yik Yak, Secret and Whisper let people share things anonymously or quasi-anonymously whereas Random let the user to explore the web anonymously.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Some email providers, like Tuta also offer the ability to create anonymous email accounts which do not require any personal information from the account holder.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Other sites, however, including Facebook and Google+, ask users to sign in with their legal names.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In the case of Google+, this requirement led to a controversy known as the nymwars.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The prevalence of cyberbullying is often attributed to relative Internet anonymity, due to the fact that potential offenders are able to mask their identities and prevent themselves from being caught.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] A principal in a high school stated that comments made on these anonymous sites are "especially vicious and hurtful since there is no way to trace their source and it can be disseminated widely.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] "Cyberbullying, as opposed to general bullying, is still a widely-debated area of Internet freedom in several states.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Though Internet anonymity can provide a harmful environment through which people can hurt others, anonymity can allow for a much safer and relaxed internet experience.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In a study conducted at Carnegie Mellon University, 15 out of 44 participants stated that they choose to be anonymous online because of a prior negative experience during which they did not maintain an anonymous presence.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Such experiences include stalking, releasing private information by an opposing school political group, or tricking an individual into traveling to another country for a job that did not exist.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Participants in this study stated that they were able to avoid their previous problems by using false identification online.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] David Chaum is considered "the father of online anonymity".
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In the early 1980s, while a computer scientist at Berkeley, Chaum predicted the world in which computer networks would make mass surveillance a possibility.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Joss Wright explains: "David Chaum was very ahead of his time.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] He predicted in the early 1980s concerns that would arise on the internet 15 or 20 years later." However, there are some who consider anonymity on the Internet as a danger for our society as a whole.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] David Davenport, an assistant professor in the Computer Engineering Department of Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey, considers that when anonymous online communication is allowed, the fabric of our society is at risk.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] "Accountability requires those responsible for any misconduct be identified and brought to justice.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] However, if people remain anonymous, by definition, they cannot be identified, making it impossible to hold them accountable." he says.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Michael Froomkin says: "The regulation of anonymous and pseudonymous communications promises to be one of the most important and contentious Internet-related issues of the next decade".
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity and pseudonymity can be used for good and bad purposes.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] And anonymity can in many cases be desirable for one person and not desirable for another person.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] A company may, for example, not like an employee to divulge information about improper practices within the company, but society as a whole may find it important that such improper practices are publicly exposed.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The border between illegal and legal but offensive use is not very sharp, and varies depending on the law in each country.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymous (used as a mass noun) is a loosely associated international network of activist and hacktivist entities.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] A website nominally associated with the group describes it as "an internet gathering" with "a very loose and decentralized command structure that operates on ideas rather than directives".
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The group became known for a series of well-publicized publicity stunts and distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attacks on government, religious, and corporate websites.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] An image commonly associated with Anonymous is the "man without a head" represents leaderless organization and anonymity.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity is perceived as a right by many, especially the anonymity in the internet communications.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The partial right for anonymity is legally protected to various degrees in different jurisdictions.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The tradition of anonymous speech is older than the United States.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Founders Alexander Hamilton, James Madison, and John Jay wrote *The Federalist Papers* under the pseudonym "Publius" and "the Federal Farmer" spoke up in rebuttal.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The US Supreme Court has repeatedly recognized rights to speak anonymously derived from the First Amendment.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The pressure on anonymous communication has grown substantially after the 2001 terrorist attack on the World Trade Center and the subsequent new political climate.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] An above-mentioned 1995 Supreme Court ruling in *McIntyre v.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Ohio Elections Commission* reads: *"(...) protections for anonymous speech are vital to democratic discourse.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Allowing dissenters to shield their identities frees them to express critical minority views . . .
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity is a shield from the tyranny of the majority. . . .
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] However, anonymous online speech is not without limits.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] It is clearly demonstrated in a case from 2008, one in which the defendant stated on a law-school discussion board that two women should be raped, an anonymous poster's comments may extend beyond free speech protections.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In the case, a Connecticut federal court must apply a standard to decide whether the poster's identity should be revealed.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] There are several tests, however, that the court could apply when considering this issue.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The right to internet anonymity is also covered by European legislation that recognizes the fundamental right to data protection, freedom of expression, freedom of impression.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The European Union Charter of Fundamental Rights recognizes in Article.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] 8 (Title II: "Freedoms") the right of everyone to protection of personal data concerning him.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The right to privacy is now essentially the individual's right to have and to maintain control over information about him.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] One of the most controversial international legal acts, regarding this subject is Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement (ACTA).
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] As of February 2015, the treaty was signed -but not all ratified- by 31 states as well as the European Union.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Japan was on 4 October 2012 the first to ratify the treaty.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] It creates an international regime for imposing civil and criminal penalties on Internet counterfeiting and copyright infringement.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Although ACTA is intentionally vague, leaving signatories to draw precise rules themselves, critics say it could mean innocent travellers having their laptops searched for unlicensed music, or being jailed for carrying a generic drug.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Infringers could be liable for the total loss of potential sales (implying that everyone who buys a counterfeit product would have bought the real thing).
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] It applies to unintentional use of copyright material.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] It puts the onus on website owners to ensure they comply with laws across several territories.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] It has been negotiated secretively and outside established international trade bodies, despite EU criticisms.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The history of anonymous expression in political dissent is both long and with important effect, as in the Letters of Junius or Voltaire's *Candide*, or scurrilous as in pasquinades.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In the tradition of anonymous British political criticism, *The Federalist Papers* were anonymously authored by three of America's Founding Fathers.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Without the public discourse on the controversial contents of the U.S.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Constitution, ratification would likely have taken much longer as individuals worked through the issues.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] The United States Declaration of Independence, however, was not anonymous.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] If it had been unsigned, it might well have been less effective.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] John Perry Barlow, Joichi Ito, and other U.S. bloggers express a very strong support for anonymous editing as one of the basic requirements of open politics as conducted on the Internet.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Some seem to want to avoid the "limelight" of popularity and to live private lives, such as Thomas Pynchon, J.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Salinger, De Onbekende Beeldhouwer (an anonymous sculptor whose exhibited work in Amsterdam attracted strong attention in the 1980s and 1990s), and by DJ duo Daft Punk (1993-2021).
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] For street artist Banksy, "anonymity is vital to him because graffiti is illegal".
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Anonymity has been used in music by avant-garde ensemble The Residents, Jandek (until 2004), costumed comedy rock band The Radioactive Chicken Heads, and DJs Deadmau5 (1998–present) and Marshmello (2015–2017).
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] This is frequently applied in fiction, from The Lone Ranger, Superman, and Batman, where a hidden identity is assumed.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Suppose that only Alice, Bob, and Carol have keys to a bank safe and that, one day, contents of the safe go missing (lock not violated).
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Without additional information, we cannot know for sure whether it was Alice, Bob or Carol who emptied the safe.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] Notably, each element in {Alice, Bob, Carol} could be the perpetrator with a probability of 1.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] However, as long as none of them was convicted with 100% certainty, we must hold that the perpetrator remains anonymous and that the attribution of the probability of 1 to one of the players has to remain undecided.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] If Carol has a definite alibi at the time of perpetration, then we may deduce that it must have been either Alice or Bob who emptied the safe.
[src:alfred-schütz/anonymisation] In this particular case, the perpetrator is not completely anonymous anymore, as both Alice and Bob now know "who did it" with a probability of 1.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] Gurwitsch was born in Vilna, Vilna Governorate, Russian Empire, on 17 January 1901 to a Lithuanian Jewish family.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] His family moved to Danzig in 1905 or 1906 to escape pogroms.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] He enrolled in the University of Berlin in 1918, where he studied under Carl Stumpf.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] In the early 1929s, he studied under Edmund Husserl at the University of Göttingen and with Adhémar Gelb and Kurt Goldstein at the University of Frankfurt am Main.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] Gurwitsch completed his doctorate at Göttingen in 1928 on *Phänomenologie der Thematik und des reinen Ich* under Moritz Geiger.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] Gurwitsch wrote on the relations between phenomenology and Gestalt psychology, and in the problems of the organization of consciousness.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] In particular, he distinguished between the theme, the thematic context and the margin.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] This is the core of his theory of the field of consciousness.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] He also has his own theory of the noema, the horizon and the transcendental ego.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] Gurwitsch was an important influence on Maurice Merleau-Ponty.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] He taught at the University of Paris (at the Institut d'Histoire des Sciences et des Techniques) from 1933 until he was forced to emigrate in 1940, where Merleau-Ponty attended his lectures.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] He taught at Brandeis University in the mid-1950s.
[src:alfred-schütz/aron-gurwitsch] He taught at The New School's Graduate Faculty of Social and Political Science from 1959 to 1973.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Austria-Hungary was one of Europe's major powers, and was the second-largest country in Europe in area (after Russia) and the third-most populous (after Russia and the German Empire), while being among the 10 most populous countries worldwide.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Empire built up the fourth-largest machine-building industry in the world.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] With the exception of the territory of the Bosnian Condominium, the Empire of Austria and the Kingdom of Hungary were separate sovereign countries in international law.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] At its core was the dual monarchy, which was a real union between Cisleithania, the northern and western parts of the former Austrian Empire, and Transleithania, which corresponded to the medieval territories of the Kingdom of Hungary.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Following the 1867 reforms, the Austrian and Hungarian states were co-equal in power.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The two countries conducted unified diplomatic and defence policies.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] For these purposes, "common" ministries of foreign affairs and defence were maintained under the monarch's direct authority, as was a third finance ministry responsible only for financing the two "common" portfolios.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] A third component of the union was the Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia, an autonomous region under the Hungarian crown, which negotiated the Croatian–Hungarian Settlement in 1868.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] After 1878, Bosnia and Herzegovina came under Austro-Hungarian joint military and civilian rule until it was fully annexed in 1908, provoking the Bosnian crisis.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Austria-Hungary was one of the Central Powers in World War I, which began with an Austro-Hungarian war declaration on the Kingdom of Serbia on 28 July 1914.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] It was already effectively dissolved by the time the military authorities signed the armistice of Villa Giusti on 3 November 1918.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The dual monarchy has been anachronistically often called simply *Austria*, referring to the main hereditary lands of the ruling Austrian Habsburgs and particularly to the Austrian Empire, which the dual monarchy emerged from.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The realm's full name used in internal administration was **The Kingdoms and Lands Represented in the Imperial Council and the Lands of the Holy Hungarian Crown of St.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The state used internally the names *k. u. k.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Monarchie* (English: k. u. k. monarchy) (in detail German: *Kaiserliche und königliche Monarchie Österreich-Ungarn*; Hungarian: *Császári és Királyi Osztrák–Magyar Monarchia*).
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Following Hungary's defeat against the Ottoman Empire in the Battle of Mohács of 1526, the Habsburg Empire became more involved in the Kingdom of Hungary, and subsequently assumed the Hungarian throne.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] However, as the Ottomans expanded further into Hungary, the Habsburgs came to control only a small north-western portion of the former kingdom's territory.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Eventually, following the Treaty of Passarowitz in 1718, all former territories of the Hungarian kingdom were ceded from the Ottomans to the Habsburgs.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In the revolutions of 1848, the Kingdom of Hungary called for greater self-government and later even independence from the Austrian Empire.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The ensuing Hungarian Revolution of 1848 was crushed by the Austrian military with Russian military assistance, and the level of autonomy that the Hungarian state had enjoyed was replaced with absolutist rule from Vienna.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] This further increased Hungarian resentment of the Habsburg dominion.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] These twin defeats gave the Hungarians the opportunity to remove the shackles of absolutist rule.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Realizing the need to compromise with Hungary in order to retain its great power status, the central government in Vienna began negotiations with the Hungarian political leaders, led by Ferenc Deák.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Hungarians maintained that the April Laws were still valid, but conceded that under the Pragmatic Sanction of 1713, foreign affairs and defence were "common" to Austria and Hungary.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On 20 March 1867, the newly re-established Hungarian parliament at Pest started to negotiate the new laws to be accepted on 30 March.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] However, Hungarian leaders received word that the Emperor's formal coronation as King of Hungary on 8 June had to have taken place in order for the laws to be enacted within the lands of the Holy Crown of Hungary.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On 28 July, Franz Joseph, in his new capacity as King of Hungary, approved and promulgated the new laws, which officially gave birth to the Dual Monarchy.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Austro-Prussian War was ended by the Peace of Prague (1866) which settled the "German question" in favor of a Lesser German Solution.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Count Friedrich Ferdinand von Beust, who was the foreign minister from 1866 to 1871, hated the Prussian chancellor, Otto von Bismarck, who had repeatedly outmaneuvered him.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Beust looked to France for avenging Austria's defeat and attempted to negotiate with Emperor Napoleon III of France and Italy for an anti-Prussian alliance, but no terms could be reached.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The decisive victory of the Prusso-German armies in the Franco-Prussian war and the subsequent founding of the German Empire ended all hope of re-establishing Austrian influence in Germany, and Beust retired.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] After being forced out of Germany and Italy, the Dual Monarchy turned to the Balkans, which were in tumult as nationalistic movements were gaining strength and demanding independence.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Both Russia and Austria–Hungary saw an opportunity to expand in this region.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Russia took on the role of protector of Slavs and Orthodox Christians.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Austria envisioned a multi-ethnic, religiously diverse empire under Vienna's control.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Count Gyula Andrássy, a Hungarian who was Foreign Minister (1871–1879), made the centerpiece of his policy one of opposition to Russian expansion in the Balkans and blocking Serbian ambitions to dominate a new South Slav federation.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] He wanted Germany to ally with Austria, not Russia.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Russian Pan-Slavic organizations sent aid to the Balkan rebels and so pressured the tsar's government to declare war on the Ottoman Empire in 1877 in the name of protecting Orthodox Christians.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Unable to mediate between the Ottoman Empire and Russia over the control of Serbia, Austria–Hungary declared neutrality when the conflict between the two powers escalated into a war.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] With help from Romania and Greece, Russia defeated the Ottomans and with the Treaty of San Stefano tried to create a large pro-Russian Bulgaria.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] This treaty sparked an international uproar that almost resulted in a general European war.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Austria–Hungary and Britain feared that a large Bulgaria would become a Russian satellite that would enable the tsar to dominate the Balkans.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] British Prime Pinister Benjamin Disraeli moved warships into position against Russia to halt the advance of Russian influence in the eastern Mediterranean so close to Britain's route through the Suez Canal.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Treaty of San Stefano was seen in Austria as much too favourable for Russia and its Orthodox-Slavic goals.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] At the Congress of Berlin in 1878 Gyula Andrássy (Minister of Foreign Affairs), with British support, managed to force Russia to reduce its excessive demands in the Balkans.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] As a result, Greater Bulgaria was broken up and remained under nominal Ottoman control, Serbia, Montenegro and Romania became fully independent and Austria occupied (but did not annex) the provinces of Bosnia and Herzegovina, a predominantly Slavic area.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The occupation required 150,000 troops and several weeks of fighting; the provinces were put under the administration of the Ministry of Finance.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In that year, with Britain's support, Austria–Hungary stationed troops in Bosnia to prevent the Russians from expanding into nearby Serbia.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In another measure to keep the Russians out of the Balkans, Austria–Hungary formed an alliance, the Mediterranean Entente, with Britain and Italy in 1887 and concluded mutual defence pacts with Germany in 1879 and Romania in 1883 against a possible Russian attack.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Following the Congress of Berlin the European powers attempted to guarantee stability through a complex series of alliances and treaties.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Anxious about Balkan instability and Russian aggression, and to counter French interests in Europe, Austria–Hungary forged a defensive alliance with Germany in October 1879 and in May 1882.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In October 1882 Italy joined this partnership in the Triple Alliance largely because of Italy's imperial rivalries with France.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Tensions between Russia and Austria–Hungary remained high, so Bismarck replaced the League of the Three Emperors with the Reinsurance Treaty with Russia to keep the Habsburgs from recklessly starting a war over Pan-Slavism.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Sandžak-Raška / Novibazar region was under Austro-Hungarian occupation between 1878 and 1909, when it was returned to the Ottoman Empire, before being ultimately divided between kingdoms of Montenegro and Serbia.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The monarchy eventually annexed Bosnia and Herzegovina in October 1908 as a common holding of Cisleithania and Transleithania under the control of the Imperial & Royal finance ministry rather than attaching it to either territorial government.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The annexation in 1908 led some in Vienna to contemplate combining Bosnia and Herzegovina with Croatia to form a third Slavic component of the monarchy.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The deaths of Franz Joseph's brother, Maximilian (1867), and his only son, Rudolf, made the Emperor's nephew, Franz Ferdinand, heir to the throne.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Archduke was rumoured to have been an advocate for this trialism as a means to limit the power of the Hungarian aristocracy.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In performance of this promise a constitution was promulgated in 1910.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The principal players in the Bosnian Crisis of 1908–09 were the foreign ministers of Austria and Russia, Alois Lexa von Aehrenthal and Alexander Izvolsky.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Both were motivated by political ambition; the first would emerge successful, and the latter would be broken by the crisis.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Along the way, they would drag Europe to the brink of war in 1909.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] They would also divide Europe into the two armed camps that would go to war in July 1914.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Aehrenthal had started with the assumption that the Slavic minorities could never come together, and the Balkan League would never cause any damage to Austria.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] He turned down an Ottoman proposal for an alliance that would include Austria, Turkey, and Romania.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] However, his policies alienated the Bulgarians, who turned instead to Russia and Serbia.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Although Austria had no intention to embark on additional expansion to the south, Aehrenthal encouraged speculation to that effect, expecting that it would paralyze the Balkan states.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Instead, it incited them to feverish activity to create a defensive block to stop Austria.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] A series of grave miscalculations at the highest level thus significantly strengthened Austria's enemies.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In 1914, Slavic militants in Bosnia rejected Austria's plan to fully absorb the area; they assassinated the Austrian heir and precipitated World War I.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The 28 June 1914 assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand in the Bosnian capital, Sarajevo, excessively intensified the existing traditional religion-based ethnic hostilities in Bosnia.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] However, in Sarajevo itself, Austrian authorities encouraged violence against the Serb residents, which resulted in anti-Serb riots in Sarajevo, in which Catholic Croats and Bosnian Muslims killed two and damaged numerous Serb-owned buildings.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Writer Ivo Andrić referred to the violence as the "Sarajevo frenzy of hate." Violent actions against ethnic Serbs were organized not only in Sarajevo but also in many other larger Austro-Hungarian cities in modern-day Croatia and Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Austro-Hungarian authorities in Bosnia and Herzegovina imprisoned and extradited approximately 5,500 prominent Serbs, 700 to 2,200 of whom died in prison.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Four hundred sixty Serbs were sentenced to death and a predominantly Muslim special militia known as the *Schutzkorps* was established and carried out the persecution of Serbs.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The foreign ministry of Austro-Hungarian Empire sent ambassador László Szőgyény to Potsdam, where he inquired about the standpoint of the German emperor, Wilhelm II, on 5 July and received a supportive response.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The leaders of Austria–Hungary therefore decided to confront Serbia militarily before it could incite a revolt; using the assassination as an excuse, they presented a list of ten demands called the July Ultimatum, expecting Serbia would never accept.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] When Serbia accepted nine of the ten demands but only partially accepted the remaining one, Austria–Hungary declared war.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Franz Joseph I finally followed the urgent counsel of his top advisers.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Over the course of July and August 1914, these events caused the start of World War I, as Russia mobilized in support of Serbia, setting off a series of counter-mobilizations.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In support of his German ally, on Thursday, 6 August 1914, Emperor Franz Joseph signed the declaration of war on Russia.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Italy initially remained neutral, despite its alliance with Austria–Hungary.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In 1915, it switched to the side of the Entente powers, hoping to gain territory from its former ally.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Empire played a relatively passive diplomatic role in the war, as it was increasingly dominated and controlled by Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The only goal was to punish Serbia and try to stop the ethnic breakup of the Empire, and it completely failed.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Starting in late 1916 the new Emperor Karl removed the pro-German officials and opened peace overtures to the Allies, whereby the entire war could be ended by compromise, or perhaps Austria would make a separate peace from Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The main effort was vetoed by Italy, which had been promised large slices of Austria for joining the Allies in 1915.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Austria was only willing to turn over the Trentino region but nothing more.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Karl was seen as a defeatist, which weakened his standing at home and with both the Allies and Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The heavily rural empire did have a small industrial base, but its major contributions were manpower and food.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Nevertheless, Austria–Hungary was more urbanized (25%) than its actual opponents in the war, like the Russian Empire (13.4%), Serbia (13.2%) or Romania (18.8%).
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Furthermore, the Austro-Hungarian Empire had also more industrialized economy and higher GDP per capita than the Kingdom of Italy, which was economically the far most developed actual opponent of the Empire.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On the home front, food grew scarcer and scarcer, as did heating fuel.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Hungary, with its heavy agricultural base, was somewhat better fed.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The army conquered productive agricultural areas in Romania and elsewhere, but refused to allow food shipments to civilians back home.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Morale fell every year, and the diverse nationalities gave up on the empire and looked for ways to establish their own nation states.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Inflation soared, from an index of 129 in 1914 to 1589 in 1918, wiping out the cash savings of the middle class.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In terms of war damage to the economy, the war consumed about 20 percent of the gross domestic product.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The dead soldiers amounted to about four percent of the 1914 labor force, and the wounded ones to another six percent.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Compared to the major countries in the war, the death and casualty rates were toward the high end regarding the present-day territory of Austria.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] By summer 1918, "Green Cadres" of army deserters formed armed bands in the hills of Croatia-Slavonia, and civil authority disintegrated.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] By late October, violence and massive looting erupted, and there were efforts to form peasant republics.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] However, the Croatian political leadership was focused on creating a new state (Yugoslavia) and worked with the advancing Serbian army to impose control and end the uprisings.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Empire conscripted 7.8 million soldiers during the war.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] General von Hötzendorf was the Chief of the Austro-Hungarian General Staff.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Franz Joseph I, who was much too old to command the army, appointed Archduke Friedrich von Österreich-Teschen as Supreme Army Commander (Armeeoberkommandant), but asked him to give Von Hötzendorf freedom to take any decisions.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Von Hötzendorf remained in effective command of the military forces until Emperor Karl I took supreme command himself in late 1916 and dismissed Conrad von Hötzendorf in 1917.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Meanwhile, economic conditions on the home front deteriorated rapidly.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The empire depended on agriculture, and agriculture depended on the heavy labor of millions of men who were now in the army.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Food production fell, the transportation system became overcrowded, and industrial production could not successfully handle the overwhelming need for munitions.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Germany provided a great deal of help, but it was not enough.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Furthermore, the political instability of the multiple ethnic groups within the empire now ripped apart any hope for national consensus in support of the war.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Increasingly there was a demand for breaking up the empire and setting up autonomous national states based on historic, language-based cultures.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The new emperor sought peace terms from the Allies, but his initiatives were vetoed by Italy.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] At the start of the war, the army was divided into two: the smaller part attacked Serbia, while the larger part fought against the formidable Imperial Russian Army.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The invasion of Serbia in 1914 was a disaster: by the end of the year, the Austro-Hungarian Army had taken no territory, but had lost 227,000 out of a total force of 450,000 men.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] However, in the autumn of 1915, the Serbian Army was defeated by the Central Powers, which led to the occupation of Serbia.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Near the end of 1915, in a massive rescue operation involving more than 1,000 trips made by Italian, French and British steamers, 260,000 Serb soldiers were transported to Brindisi and Corfu, where they waited for the chance of the victory of Allied powers to reclaim their country.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Corfu hosted the Serbian government in exile after the collapse of Serbia and served as a supply base for the Greek front.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In April 1916 a large number of Serbian troops were transported in British and French naval vessels from Corfu to mainland Greece.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The contingent numbering over 120,000 relieved a much smaller army at the Macedonian front and fought alongside British and French troops.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On the Eastern front, the war started out equally poorly.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The government accepted the Polish proposal of establishing the Supreme National Committee as the Polish central authority within the empire, responsible for the formation of the Polish Legions, an auxiliary military formation within the Austro-Hungarian Army.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Austro-Hungarian Army was defeated at the Battle of Lemberg and the great fortress city of Przemyśl was besieged and fell in March 1915.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In summer 1915, the Austro-Hungarian Army, under a unified command with the Germans, participated in the successful Gorlice–Tarnów Offensive.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] From June 1916, the Russians focused their attacks on the Austro-Hungarian Army in the Brusilov Offensive, recognizing the latter's numerical inferiority.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] By the end of September 1916, Austria–Hungary mobilized and concentrated new divisions, and the successful Russian advance was halted and slowly repelled; but the Austrian armies took heavy losses (about 1 million men) and never recovered.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Nevertheless, the huge losses in men and materiel inflicted on the Russians during the offensive contributed greatly to the Russian Revolution of 1917 and caused an economic crash in the Russian Empire.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Act of 5 November 1916 was then proclaimed to the Poles jointly by the Emperors Wilhelm II of Germany and Franz Joseph of Austria-Hungary.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] This act promised the creation of the Kingdom of Poland out of the territory of Congress Poland, envisioned by its authors as a puppet state controlled by the Central Powers, with the nominal authority vested in the Regency Council.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The origin of that document was the dire need to draft new recruits from German-occupied Poland for the war with Russia.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Battle of Zborov (1917) was the first significant action of the Czechoslovak Legions, which fought for the independence of Czechoslovakia against the Austro-Hungarian Army.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In May 1915, Italy attacked Austria–Hungary.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Italy was the only military opponent of Austria–Hungary which had a similar degree of industrialization and economic level; moreover, her army was numerous (≈1,000,000 men were immediately fielded), but suffered from poor leadership, training and organization.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Chief of Staff Luigi Cadorna marched his army towards the Isonzo River, hoping to seize Ljubljana, and to eventually threaten Vienna.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] However, the Royal Italian Army were halted on the river, where four battles took place over five months (23 June – 2 December 1915).
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The fight was extremely bloody and exhausting for both sides.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On 15 May 1916, Austrian Chief of Staff Conrad von Hötzendorf launched the *Strafexpedition* ("punitive expedition"): the Austrians broke through the front and occupied the Asiago plateau.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Italians managed to resist and in a counteroffensive seized Gorizia on 9 August.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Nonetheless, they had to stop on the Carso, a few kilometres away from the border.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] At this point, several months of indecisive trench warfare ensued (analogous to the Western front).
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] As the Russian Empire collapsed as a result of the Bolshevik Revolution and the Russians ended their involvement in the war, Germans and Austrians were able to transfer much of their manpower to the Western and Southern fronts from the erstwhile Eastern fighting.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On 24 October 1917, Austrians (now enjoying decisive German support) attacked at Caporetto using new infiltration tactics; although they advanced more than 100 km (62.14 mi) in the direction of Venice and gained considerable supplies, they were halted and could not cross the Piave River.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Italy, although suffering massive casualties, recovered from the blow, and a coalition government under Vittorio Emanuele Orlando was formed.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Italy also enjoyed the support of the Entente: by 1918, large amounts of war materials and a few auxiliary American, British, and French divisions arrived in the Italian battle zone.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Cadorna was replaced by General Armando Diaz; under his command, the Italians retook the initiative and won the decisive Second Battle of the Piave River (15–23 June 1918), in which some 60,000 Austrian and 43,000 Italian soldiers were killed.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The final battle at Vittorio Veneto was lost by 31 October 1918 and the armistice was signed at Villa Giusti on 3 November.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On 27 August 1916, Romania declared war against Austria–Hungary.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Within three months of the war, the Central Powers approached Bucharest, the Romanian capital.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On 6 December, Bucharest was captured, and part of the population moved to the unoccupied Romanian territory, in Moldavia, together with the Romanian government, royal court and public authorities, which relocated to Iași.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In 1917, after several defensive victories (managing to stop the German-Austro-Hungarian advance), with Russia's withdrawal from the war following the October Revolution, Romania was forced to drop out of the war.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Although the Kingdom of Hungary comprised only 42% of the population of Austria–Hungary, the thin majority— more than 3.8 million soldiers—of the Austro-Hungarian armed forces were conscripted from the Kingdom of Hungary during the First World War.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Roughly 600,000 soldiers were killed in action, and 700,000 soldiers were wounded in the war.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Austria–Hungary held on for years, as the Hungarian half provided sufficient supplies for the military to continue to wage war.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] This was shown in a transition of power after which the Hungarian prime minister, Count István Tisza, and foreign minister, Count István Burián, had decisive influence over the internal and external affairs of the monarchy.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] By late 1916, food supply from Hungary became intermittent and the government sought an armistice with the Entente powers.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] However, this failed as Britain and France no longer had any regard for the integrity of the monarchy due to Austro-Hungarian support for Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The setbacks that the Austrian army suffered in 1914 and 1915 can be attributed to a large extent by the incompetence of the Austrian high command.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] After attacking Serbia, its forces soon had to be withdrawn to protect its eastern frontier against Russia's invasion, while German units were engaged in fighting on the Western Front.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] This resulted in a greater than expected loss of men in the invasion of Serbia.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Furthermore, it became evident that the Austrian high command had had no plans for possible continental war and that the army and navy were also ill-equipped to handle such a conflict.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In the last two years of the war the Austro-Hungarian armed forces lost all ability to act independently of Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] As of 7 September 1916, the German emperor was given full control of all the armed forces of the Central Powers and Austria-Hungary effectively became a satellite of Germany.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Austrians viewed the German army favorably; on the other hand, by 1916 the general belief in Germany was that Germany, in its alliance with Austria–Hungary, was "shackled to a corpse".
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The operational capability of the Austro-Hungarian army was seriously affected by supply shortages, low morale and a high casualty rate, and by the army's composition of multiple ethnicities with different languages and customs.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] By 1918, the economic situation had deteriorated and governmental failure on the homefront ended popular support for the war.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Austro-Hungarian monarchy collapsed with dramatic speed in the autumn of 1918.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Leftist and pacifist political movements organized strikes in factories, and uprisings in the army had become commonplace.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] As the war went on, the ethnic unity declined; the Allies encouraged breakaway demands from minorities and the Empire faced disintegration.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] With apparent Allied victory approaching, nationalist movements seized ethnic resentment to erode social unity.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The military breakdown of the Italian front marked the start of the rebellion for the numerous ethnicities who made up the multiethnic Empire, as they refused to keep on fighting for a cause that now appeared senseless.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Emperor had lost much of his power to rule, as his realm disintegrated.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] However, on 18 October, United States Secretary of State Robert Lansing replied that autonomy for the nationalities – the tenth of the Fourteen Points – was no longer enough.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] In fact, a Czechoslovak provisional government had joined the Allies on 14 October.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The South Slavs in both halves of the monarchy had already declared in favor of uniting with Serbia in a large South Slav state in the 1917 Corfu Declaration signed by members of the Yugoslav Committee.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] The Croatians had begun disregarding orders from Budapest earlier in October.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] Lansing's response was, in effect, the death certificate of Austria–Hungary.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] During the Italian battles, the Czechoslovaks and Southern Slavs declared their independence.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] With defeat in the war imminent after the Italian offensive in the Battle of Vittorio Veneto on 24 October, Czech politicians peacefully took over command in Prague on 28 October (later declared the birth of Czechoslovakia) and followed up in other major cities in the next few days.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On 30 October, the Slovaks did the same.
[src:alfred-schütz/austria-hungary-p01] On 29 October, the Slavs in both portions of what remained of Austria–Hungary proclaimed the State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs and declared that their ultimate intention was to unite with Serbia and Montenegro in a large South Slav state.
